<HEADLINE> Construction of Key Railway Roads in Southwest China Commences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Construction of two railway trunk
lines in southwest China started here today.
</P>
<P>
One railway road links Neijiang City in southwest China's
Sichuan Province with Kunming, capital of Yunnan Province in the
same region.
</P>
<P>
The 879-km-long road, one of the state-listed key projects for
the 1996-2000 period, will cost an estimated investment of 11.6
billion yuan (1.4 billion U.S. dollars), which will be shared by
the Ministry of Railways and the governments of Sichuan, Guizhou
and Yunnan provinces.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to open to traffic in 2001 and be
transformed into an electrified line in the following year with a
designed transport capacity of 17 million tons a year.
</P>
<P>
Another project is the transformation of a double-track railway
road between Zhuzhou, in central China's Hunan Province, and
Liupanshui in southwest China's Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
It will become an electrified road upon completion in 2002. The
project will cost an investment of 23 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Operation of the two roads will alleviate traffic jam in
southwest China and cut the distance between Chengdu, capital of
Sichuan Province, and Fangchenggang in Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
region by 385 km.  
</P>
</TEXT>
