<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Lowers Statutory Reserve Requirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia announced Friday
that it will lower the Statutory Reserve Requirement (SRR) of
merchant banks, commercial banks and finance companies in the
country by two percentage points to eight percent of their
eligible liabilities from July 1.
</P>
<P>
Bank Negara (Central Bank) said in a statement that the measure
is aimed at further reducing the cost of funds to banking
institutions and improving the efficiency of the intermediation
process in providing financing to productive economic activities.
</P>
<P>
It said the reduction in the SRR represents part of a series of
measures that would be taken to ensure that the Malaysian economy
does not spiral into a major economic slowdown while maintaining
macroeconomic objectives announced earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Explaining that the lower funding cost would enable
institutions to lower their lending rates, the bank said a two
percentage points reduction in SRR to eight percent would reduce
the base lending rate (BLR) of the commercial banks by 0.21
percent and that of finance companies by 0.27 percent.
</P>
<P>
The reduction in SRR would release about 8.0 billion ringgit
(about 2 billion U.S. dollars) of funds to the banking
institutions, the liquidity in the interbank market would be
closely monitored and the three-month Bank Negara Malaysia
intervention rate would remain unchanged, it added.
</P>
<P>
On February 16, the SRR was cut from 13.5 percent to the
current 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the interest rate policy would have to
take into consideration the significant deceleration in monetary
and credit growth and the slowdown in economic activity in the
first half of 1998 as well as the need to maintain exchange rate
stability.
</P>
<P>
Credit growth of the banking system slowed down from 30.4
percent at the end of June 1997 to 12 percent at the end of May
1998 while Malaysia's real gross domestic product (GDP) declined
by 1.8 percent in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The central bank noted that inflation during April and May this
year, however, has stabilized in the region of 5.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
