<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Leader Elected Into New N. Irish Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams became
one of the first members to be elected to the new Northern Ireland
Assembly Friday, election officials said.
</P>
<P>
Adams, whose party is the political wing of the Irish
Republican Army (IRA), took one of six seats in the strongly Roman
Catholic West Belfast constituency.
</P>
<P>
Adams was elected in the first of several counts due to take
place in Belfast's City Hall for the four constituencies in the
city out of 18 across the British-ruled province.
</P>
<P>
The election paves the way for Adams to become a minister in a
12-member ruling executive at the head of a 108-seat assembly that
will give the province its first taste of self-rule in a
generation.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time that Sinn Fein has taken up seats in
a provincial administration under British sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
Martin Mcguinness, one of Sinn Fein's top leaders, also won a
seat in the assembly in the Mid Ulster constituency.
</P>
<P>
Estimates are that the total voter turn-out was around 70
percent -- lower than last month's referendum on the peace
agreement, but higher than last year's general elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
