<HEADLINE> Yeltsin to Follow Duma Debates on Anti-Crisis Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
would stay in Moscow next week to follow Duma debates on a
government-proposed program, the Kremlin said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Prompting Yeltsin to delay his pre-scheduled overseas tour is
the agenda of Duma, or the lower house of parliament, to
deliberate on ways to handle the country's financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The president did not think it would be proper for his absence
for four days when his country was faced with a crisis, his Press
Secretary Sergei Yastrzhembsky told the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin initially planned to start on July 1 a visit to
Kazakhstan. And on July 3, he would join a summit meeting with his
counterparts from China, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
Late Thursday, the Kremlin announced postponing the trip to
September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
