<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sidebar: Clinton's First Full Day Visit in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Following are some titbits in the
first full day U.S. President Bill Clinton spent in China:
</P>
<P>
-- Shopping at Handicraft Stands
</P>
<P>
People of Xiahe village near the site of the terra-cotta
warriors are known for their business mind, and today they
impressed visiting U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Sure they wouldn't miss the big chance today when the U.S.
president came to visit their village in the outskirts of Xi'an.
They lined up hand-made clothing and cute little toys on the
stands along the road to the village.
</P>
<P>
Clinton walked up to one of the stands for a closer look at the
goods and apparently was very interested in the handicrafts made
of bright red home-woven cloth with Chinese traditional designs
such as dragons and spiders.
</P>
<P>
"How much is this?" the president asked, pointing at a wall
decoration composed of miniatures of the 12 animals representing
the Chinese lunar year.
</P>
<P>
"Twenty yuan (around 2.5 U.S. dollars)," answered the owner of
the stand, a young women named He Yanhong.
</P>
<P>
The president bought one.
</P>
<P>
"Twenty yuan is already a real bargain" said He, when someone
suggested she sell it at a lower price to the distinguished guest.
</P>
<P>
Many of the reporters, who came simply because the president
did, left the village wearing red baseball caps with the dragon,
pheonix, tiger on the front.
</P>
<P>
Some bought bright red vest made of homespun cloth, which is
known to local people as "Shaanxi vests."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
