<HEADLINE> Flood Hits South China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 26 (Xinhua) -- With torrential rain continuing,
many parts of south China's Guangdong Province have been hit by
heavy flood, with seven deaths reported so far.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 15 high-ways have been severed, a number of
reservoirs on the verge of collapse and many towns and villages
flooded, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
In Yangjiang City, over 100,000 people have been stranded by
flood with three deaths reported and 4,100 houses damaged; 15
towns and over 1,000 villages in Enping City are flooded with
large areas of crops destroyed; four deaths were reported in
Shaoguan City.
</P>
<P>
The flood situation is expected to worsen in coming days
as rivers are continuing to surge, said an official with the
Provincial Hydrologic Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Disaster relief operations are busy under way, according to
the provincial government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sidebar: Clinton's First Full Day Visit in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- The "Hungry, Thirsty" Await President
</P>
<P>
The professional instinct drived reporters who were able to
cover Clinton's arrival at the Beijing International Airport
within a near reach to secure a satisfying spot, but not
necessarily reminded them of their need for water and food.
</P>
<P>
Awaiting three to four hours in summer heat at the parking
field for the presidential airplane, the reporters were hungry
and thirsty. Many could not help being envious of those thoughtful
enough to bring mineral water and snacks with them.
</P>
<P>
Out of security consideration, however, the reporters who had
gone through strict security procedures were not allowed to go
out.
</P>
<P>
But the reality was that they had to be there for another two
or three hours before President Clinton could appear.
</P>
<P>
At the requests of the reporters and after consultation with the
authorities, the Chinese and U.S. security guards finally agreed
that the reporters could get on a special shuttle bus to get some
food and beverages at a nearby hostel outside the airport.
</P>
<P>
When the shuttle bus that came every half an hour reached the
parking field, the hungry and thirsty crammed into the bus.
</P>
<P>
But, again, here comes the long, strict security procedures.
</P>
<P>
-- Excavating News Clues
</P>
<P>
Though "stuck" in the place where they were allowed to stay,
reporters are still reporters.
</P>
<P>
Some used cell phones. Others exchanged information with old
buddies. And almost all were hunting for official information from
Chinese and U.S. official sources.
</P>
<P>
When an official-looking guy was surrounded by a flock of
reporters, seemingly talking about something, some more went "up
close and personal."
</P>
<P>
Then the "official" told the new comers that he and his
crowd were with a Hong Kong television, and were discussing
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
"I thought you were with the Information Department of the
Foreign Ministry (of China)," a new comer said with
disappointment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
