<HEADLINE> Improved Sino-U.S. Ties Conducive to World Peace: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan said Friday that U.S. President Bill Clinton's current
trip to China is conducive to the promotion of regional stability
and the maintenance of world peace.
</P>
<P>
Surin told Xinhua during a reception Friday night that he was
glad to see President Clinton finally made the trip despite some
different opinions about it in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The world needs active engagement of China in promoting
regional stability and maintaining world peace," the foreign
minister said.
</P>
<P>
It is not necessary at all for some people to feel disturbed
about Clinton's China visit, he added.
</P>
<P>
Surin also said that Thailand, as other countries in the world,
is very interested in Clinton's visit to China.
</P>
<P>
The trip extends a "positive message" to the world that the
role China plays in the regional and world arenas cannot be
underestimated, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
