<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Aspiration of Two Decades Satisfied (By Chen Xin) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton was
very pleased today when he succeeded in joining the head
of a Chinese "warrior" to its body.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the "warrior" could not come to life, for it was a
terra-cotta one buried more than 2,000 years ago along with the
first emperor of the Qin Dynasty (221-207 BC) who unified China
for the first time in the Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
The president, who is now on a nine-day state visit to China,
said he was very delighted to pitch in restoring a terra-cotta
warrior, enjoying a big laugh after the operation.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and his wife visited at noon today the No. 1 and No. 2
army vaults of the museum of terra-cotta warriors and the bronze
chariot and horse exhibition hall in the company of Shaanxi
Provincial Governor Cheng Andong and his wife and museum Curator
Wu Yongqi.
</P>
<P>
Clinton completed the last phase of the repair process at the
terra-cotta restoration center of the museum.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yongqi explained that many terra-cotta warriors had been
crushed or fractured after being buried for so many years. It
requires a large amount of meticulous work to restore them.
</P>
<P>
The body and head of the terra-cotta warrior joined by
Clinton today had been pieced together separately. Curator Wu
Yongqi handed the head to Clinton who in turn lifted it carefully
and placed it on the slit of the warrior's neck.
</P>
<P>
Fondling the warrior of his same stature, Clinton said it was
"perfect" and "fantastic."
</P>
<P>
The terra-cotta warriors, located 37 kilometers to the east of
Shaanxi Province's capital Xi'an, were first discovered by local
farmers digging a well in 1974. And a large-scale excavation was
carried out in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
They are among the world's most important archeological
findings in the century and regarded as the Eighth Wonder.
</P>
<P>
Pointing to the warrior he had just fixed, Clinton said that
"I've been waiting for 25 years" to come and see the warriors. He
said he had come eventually and had greater enjoyment than
expected.
</P>
<P>
He mentioned twice to the governor and curator in less than an
hour the aspiration he cherished when he was young.
</P>
<P>
In the No. 1 Army Vault there are formations of more than 6,000
terra-cotta chariot warriors and infantry troopers. The Clintons
stepped down to the basement of the vault and were reluctant to
ascend after viewing the warriors for more than a quarter of an
hour.
</P>
<P>
Before concluding his tour of the museum, Clinton signed his
name on the visitors' book, with the inscription: "Thank you for a
wonderful tour." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Beat Croatia 1-0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BORDEAUX, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Argentina beat Croatia 1-0 to
qualify into the second round as Group H winners.
</P>
<P>
Argentina will take on the runners-up of Group G while Croatia
will have to face the winners of that group.
</P>
<P>
The match between Argentina and Croatia was slow and lack-luster
with both teams concentrated on midfield and seemed not willing to
attack.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine team, which need only a draw to win the group,
adopted a counter-attack tactics while the Croatian team also lacked
motivation.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine team took one of several chances at the 36th
minutes when Hector Pineda beat a off-side trap and scored the sole
goal of the match.
</P>
<P>
In the second half, the Argentine team could have scored more
goals but Marcelo Gallardo's shot was just wide at the 75th minute.
</P>
<P>
Star striker Gabriel Batistuta, who shares the top position in
the scorers' list with Italian Vieri with four goals each, also put
on a sluggish performance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Personal Income, Spending Climb Up Strongly in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. personal incomes
picked up 0.5 percent in May but spending increased at a slightly
higher pace, the Commerce Department reported here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The increase in income, to a seasonally adjusted 7.22 trillion
U.S. dollars, reflected gains in all broad categories, including
wages and salaries, which account for more than half of income,
according to the department.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, personal consumption expenditures rose 0.6 percent,
to a seasonally adjusted 5.75 trillion dollars.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the fact that spending growth was outpacing
income growth, the U.S. savings rate dropped from 4 percent of
disposable, or after-tax, income in December last year to a
10-month low of 3.5 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
While other sectors' personal income was rising, manufacture's
was flat in May after declining 0.1 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
However, payrolls of service and distributive industries'
surged. Also rising were business owners' income, farmers' income,
transfer payments such as Social Security, rental income,
dividends and interest.
</P>
<P>
The country's spending in May rose most strongly for durable
goods, expensive items expected to last three years or longer. It
increased 2.9 percent, the most in 10 months.
</P>
<P>
Spending rose 0.4 percent for nondurable goods and 0.3 percent
for services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
