<HEADLINE> Swaziland to Launch Road Safety Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Swaziland's national road
safety council said Friday that it would launch a national road
safety campaign to curb the high incidence of road accidents in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The campaign would include road safety awareness booklets
aimed at adults, workshops for teachers to enable them to educate
pupils, radio and television programs and road safety clubs at
schools, council secretary Sibusiso Dlamini said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The country has one of the worst road accident rates in
Africa, and more than 55.6 million U.S. Dollars worth of property
was lost every year in accidents, South African Press Association
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Pedestrians should be educated as well as drivers, as half of
those involved in crashes were pedestrians, Dlamini said.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland's high road accident rate has been linked to the
country's rate of alcohol consumption, which is among the highest
in Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
