<HEADLINE> Mugabe Wants Resettlement Accelerated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Friday urged his ruling Zimbabwe African National Union Patriotic
Front (ZANU-PF) government to move fast on land redistribution
program to avoid anarchy.
</P>
<P>
He said the move by farmers in Mashonaland East and
Matebeleland North (two provinces) onto commercial farms was a
signal of what could happen countrywide.
</P>
<P>
Last week, about a thousand villagers in the two provinces
occupied several commercial farms. They are now demanding a
written undertaking from the government promising them that they
will be resettled on the farms they have invaded.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe was addressing the ZANU-PF's 34th ordinary session of
the central committee meeting, whose main topic was the land
issue, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of land has remained one of great concerns to the
majority of the people, especially as they see no real practical
or physical process on the ground," said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
"What are we afraid of? Do we fear the British, International
Monetary Fund or the World Bank and not our own people?" Mugabe
asked.
</P>
<P>
"We must strive to fulfill their right they suffered for, the
right they willingly gave up their sons and daughters in the
struggle, the right our comrades perished for during the
liberation war," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Let us not continue to lag behind the people's expectations
lest we invite anarchy into a process which so far has been going
smoothly and systematically," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some progress had been made so far with some
five million hectares of commercial land having been acquired
last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
