<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Setup of India National Security Council Recommended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A high-level task force set up
by the Indian government last April Friday recommended the
establishment of a national security council on a priority basis.
</P>
<P>
The three-member team led by former defense minister K. C. Pant
presented its report to Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee
Friday, which said management of national security had become more
pressing after India's nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
The council should comprise a cabinet committee headed by the
prime minister as the apex decision-making body, according to a
statement issued by the office of the task force chairman.
</P>
<P>
The council should include a cabinet-rank national security
adviser to the prime minister and three divisions for concurrent
functions, the report recommended.
</P>
<P>
The three concurrent functions to be performed are long-term
strategic planning, formulation of strategy of national security
coordination of current decision-making and follow-up of policy
implementation, and coordinated intelligence assessment for
national security planning and management.
</P>
<P>
The National Agenda for Governance announced by Vajpayee last
March had promised to establish a national security council which
could undertake India's first-ever strategic defense review. The
government set up the task force on April 14.
</P>
<P>
The report said the task force recognized that national
security management required integrated thinking and coordinated
application of political, military, diplomatic, scientific and
technological resources of the country to protect and promote
national security goals and objectives.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the team adopted a broad and comprehensive approach
to the concept of security, it said the proposed national security
in India's context needed to be viewed not only in military terms,
but should also include fields of domestic peace, economic
well-being and financial viability, trade policy, technological
strength and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
The planning and management of national security, therefore,
should include the relevant aspects of functioning of the six
ministries of the central government dealing with these issues,
the report added.
</P>
<P>
The organization should function within the government and be
answerable to the cabinet and parliament, said the report.
</P>
<P>
All decision-making would continue to remain within the
existing ministries and departments with the national security
council acting as the facilitator and assisting in coordination of
integrated approach to planning and management of national
security, in a holistic manner, the report recommended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
