<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Ugandan Rebels Isolated Following </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The rebels active in northern and
western Uganda have been intensifying their abduction activities
and it is these horrific abductions that put them under the quick
fire from the general public and make their lonely bases in
remote areas more isolated.
</P>
<P>
Abductions by young rebels have hit headlines in recent local
media and it gives the impression that the rebels are more
desperate than ever.
</P>
<P>
There are three groups of rebels in Uganda. The Lord
Resistance Army (LRA) rebels spearheaded by Joseph Kony, which
numbers some 1,000 in total, are active in northern districts
while the Allied Democratic Forces (ADF) and the Uganda National
Rescue Front (UNRF) II rebels take the northwestern and western
districts as their bases.
</P>
<P>
In April, LRA rebels infiltrated into northern Uganda from
their bases in southern Sudan to make abductions and loot
foodstuffs, sending the Museveni administration on alert.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, mostly young trained abductees, attacked villages
and used landmines to loot goods vehicles on roads in Gulu and
Kitgum districts.
</P>
<P>
On June 8, some 200 ADF rebels staged a surprise pre-dawn
attack on the Kichwamba Technical College in western Kabarole
district, burning over 80 students to death and abducting more
than 100 others.
</P>
<P>
On June 22, 40 girl students from a secondary school in
northern Acholi district were abducted by the LRA rebels soon
after midnight.
</P>
<P>
Two days later, the UNRF rebels abducted 15 bus passengers on
the Koboko-Yumbe-Moyo road in the north of the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
These inhuman acts of terror soon became the target of
criticism from international bodies, the Ugandan government and
civilians at large.
</P>
<P>
Members of parliament and civilians accused the government of
being responsible for the June 8 massacre because the government
army protecting the college fled in front of rebel advances.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government took the blame and at the same time
determined to flush out the rebels.
</P>
<P>
In order to wipe out the rebels, heavy military presence was
deployed in the war-torn districts and more efficient commanders
were appointed to replace the less capable. Moreover, tanks and
other efficient weapons were applied against the thugs.
</P>
<P>
However, the soldiers registered little success because of the
mountainous topography of the areas and laxities within the army.
</P>
<P>
All the setbacks in the front and threats issued by the rebels
have not in the least changed the government's mind of
eliminating the wrongdoers by force.
</P>
<P>
President Yoweri Museveni has made clear on several occasions
that the government will not talk to the rebels although there
was a strong outcry for the peace talks from some members of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
This determination can also be reflected in the sharp increase
of defense spending in the new budget presented to the parliament
by Minister of Finance Gerald Ssendaula on June 11.
</P>
<P>
In the budget, the military spending will be increased 26
percent from the current level of 120 million U.S. Dollars to 150
million Dollars, the biggest increase second only to that for
education.
</P>
<P>
In the urban areas, the authorities have beefed up security
measures against possible relentless acts of horror. More arrests
have been made in the capital Kampala recently and security is
clearly tightened in important public places.
</P>
<P>
These preventive measures may not wipe out all the rebels in
the country in a short period of time, but one thing is sure: the
rebels would face harder times under the mounting pressure from
all sides and they would be left less room for survival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
