<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Calls Alarm to Drug Addiction on Campuses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A senior Vietnamese official has
called alarm to a surge of drug addiction and trafficking among
the country's school kids and college students in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Of the 61 provinces and municipalities across Vietnam, said Le
Vu Hung, Deputy Minister of Education and Training, 56 have found
their school campuses already penetrated somehow by narcotics.
</P>
<P>
As results, 2,837 kids and students, 63 percent of them at
secondary schools, have been identified as drug addicts, Hung was
quoted as saying by a Vietnam News Agency (VNA) report Friday.
</P>
<P>
Friday is the International Day Against Drug Abuse.
</P>
<P>
To help wipe out drugs on campuses, said Huang, who chairs his
ministry's Committee for Drug-HIV/AIDS Prevention, anti-drug
programs have been in place since the 1997-98 school year.
</P>
<P>
And as a part of these programs, including educational ones,
teenagers are urged to sign a pledge to stay away from drugs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, the ministry would also mobilize schools,
administrators and local police to work together in identifying
violators and applying appropriate disciplinary measures.
</P>
<P>
The official said the ministry would also launch a health
program to offer medical checkups to college freshmen on a more
regular basis, and possible treatments if needed.
</P>
<P>
Anti-drug efforts so far have already paid off, with 855 of the
1,387 addicted students, or 62 percent, in 17 provinces and
municipalities have kicked their habits, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
