<HEADLINE> UNHCR Seeks to Help 65,000 Ethnic Albanians in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- United Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR) would seek regular access to the Serbian
province of Kosovo to help 65,000 ethnic Albanians there, said its
chief Mrs Sadako Ogata here Friday.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, aid teams from the UNHCR and the World Food
Program entered Kosovo to bring relief supplies to 600 civilians
there.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time we could really get in this region in
order to bring assistance, mostly to women and children who have
been cut off," Ogata told reporters. "We will carry on
humanitarian assistance inside Kosovo as much as we can, as long
as we are allowed."
</P>
<P>
Ogata also warned that if the Kosovo crisis worsened, "it will
certainly affect Bosnia or the whole Dayton agreement," "so we
hope it does not aggravate."
</P>
<P>
"We strongly condemn violence," she said. "We are insisting on
access. This is an area where we have to be very active in at
least the next few weeks as far as I can see." 
</P>
