<HEADLINE> Israel Urges Lebanon to Negotiate Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai Friday urged the Lebanese government to
negotiate an agreement for Israel to pull back troops from south
Lebanon, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to four Israeli soldiers wounded in south
Lebanon, Mordechai voiced hope that Lebanon will move forward
with an Israeli offer in a bid to change the situation in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel decided in April to endorse the United Nations Security
Council Resolution 425, which calls for unilateral Israeli
withdrawal from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But Israel demanded that security arrangements be reached with
the Lebanese government before it withdraws troops from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai urged Syria to help the negotiations between Israel
and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria, which stations 40,000 troops as peacekeepers
in Lebanon, have rejected the Israeli offer, insisting that the
Israeli withdrawal be unconditional.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai's call came one day after a successful swap deal
between Israel, the Lebanese Muslim group Hezbollah and the
Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
The remains of an Israeli soldier killed last September in a
botched commando raid in south Lebanon was brought back to Israel
on Thursday night. In return, Israel sent back the bodies of 40
Hezbollah fighters to Beirut and released 60 Hezbollah detainees.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a so-called security zone, with an area of 1,200
square kilometers, in south Lebanon in 1985 to allegedly protect
its northern border from cross-border attacks by Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese resistance forces are fighting to drive the Israeli
troops out of Lebanon. Heavy casualties have prompted the Jewish
state to pull out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
