<HEADLINE> Paedophile Trial Postponed by 2 Years in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Belgian Justice Ministry said
Friday that the trial of the country's alleged child kidnapper and
rapist had been postponed by two years until September 2000.
</P>
<P>
The trial was being delayed because the investigation into the
crimes of Marc Dutroux had not been completed, ministry spokesman
Eugeen van Kerchkoven said.
</P>
<P>
"At the earliest it (the trial) will be in September 2000 and
it could also be in January 2001," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dutroux was accused of raping and murdering four girls and
kidnapping two others when the country's most notorious child sex
ring was exposed in mid-1996.
</P>
<P>
The brief escape from jail in April this year caused a
sensation in Belgium and two cabinet ministers had to resign to
take the responsibility and the government set in motion a
far-reaching reform of the police and justice systems.
</P>
<P>
The chiefs of the justice and interior ministries resigned
following the escape that allowed the paedophile to remain at
large for three and a half hours before being caught again near
the borders between Belgium and Luxembourg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
