<HEADLINE> Angolan Govt Denies Any Agreement with UNITA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government Friday
denied that it had reached any agreement with the opposition
UNITA on completing the remaining tasks prescribed in the Lusaka
Peace Accord after the U.N. Security Council deadline.
</P>
<P>
Higino Carneiro, deputy chief of the government delegation in
the Joint Committee of the Angolan Peace Process, revealed the
government stand in response to the statement made by Lukamba
Gato, general secretary of the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) at a press conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government has always held that Andulo, Bailundo, Nharea
and Mungo, the four regions under UNITA's control, should be
handed over to the government on the deadline set by the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Under the Council's resolution, the task should be completed
by June 23. The Security Council Wednesday postponed the
deadline to June 30 and ruled that new sanctions including
freezing the foreign accounts of UNITA leadership, and
restricting the UNITA's diamond export, will take into effect on
July 1 if the four regions are not handed over on time.
</P>
<P>
Gato said Thursday that UNITA and the government agreed at the
June 19 meeting in Andulo that the two sides will meet again in
15 days to decide on the exact date when UNITA hands over the
four regions.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that UNITA could not hand over the four places
until after July 10.
</P>
<P>
Carneiro denied these statements, saying that the government
only stated that U.N resolutions must be adhered to, and didn't
reach any agreement on any date other than the Security Council's
deadline.
</P>
<P>
He finally noted that the only way to prevent the U.N
resolution from taking effect is for UNITA to accomplish all its
due tasks by the deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
