<HEADLINE> Russia Calls Belarus' Eviction of Ambassadors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Russia Friday called Belarus'
recent eviction of foreign ambassadors from their residence "an
undiplomatic act" and called for a solution that "takes account of
the interests of all sides."
</P>
<P>
Moscow "accepts with deep regret the conflict which has arisen
over the Drozdy compound, which has led to the departure of some
ambassadors from Belarus," the Interfax news agency quoted Russian
Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Russia has done everything possible to contain this conflict
and divert its settlement onto the course of negotiations,"
Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
The ambassadors of Britain, France, Germany, Greece, Italy and
the United States left Minsk on June 22 for consultations with
their respective foreign ministries.
</P>
<P>
The departure came after demands from Belarussian authorities
that they vacate their residence in the Drozdy compound and water
and gas supply were cut.
</P>
<P>
Belarussian authorities notified the 20 missions in early May
that work would soon be started to overhaul the compound's water
and sewage systems, which were last repaired about 40 years ago,
and asked them to either move to new buildings in central Minsk
and the Krylovo governmental compound, or begin construction of
their own buildings near Minsk.
</P>
<P>
Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko, who is in
Switzerland to attend an international economic forum, told
reporters that the real cause of the incident was Minsk's course
toward rapprochement with Russia and its staunch opposition to
NATO eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
"We do not accept a policy of lecturing and provocation,"
Lukashenko said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the West to give up its double standard in foreign
policy and look at the world with reason and self-restraint,
Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Also on Friday, before his departure to Switzerland, Lukashenko
said the ambassadors could only return "with the permission of
Belarussian authorities."
</P>
<P>
"Let them consult, but they should know they can come back only
with our permission," Interfax quoted the president as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
