<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan: Key to Solving Afghan Tragedy Lies in Ending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The key to solving te
Afghan tragedy lies in curtailing the continuous foreign
interference in the form of arms and other supplies to the warring
factions, said U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the U.N. Security Council, Annan said that for
such interference to end, the regional powers need to talk to each
other and build mutual confidence.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the supply of arms and money to
Afghanistan's warring factions, including both Taliban and the
Northern Alliance, has continued unabated during the past three
months, frustrating international mediation efforts.
</P>
<P>
The report said internal political tensions among the Afghan
factions have further complicated prospects for the resumption of
peace talks, following the failure of a U.N.-sponsored dialogue
between the two sides in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief expressed alarm at the suspension of dialogue
and the apparent start of the annual spring offensive. He called
on the Afghan factions to return to the negotiating table without
delay and on the regional powers to intensify contacts on
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and the Organization of Islamic Conference,
he said, are both ready to offer the regional powers opportunities
to enhance their mutual trust so that they can help the Afghan
people and save the entire region from the real danger of any
spillover effects from the conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
