<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea, Ethiopia Urged to Cease Hostilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, JUNE 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
adopted a resolution Friday, appealing to Eritrea and Ethiopia for
the immediate cessation of hostilities and restrait from further
use of force against each other.
</P>
<P>
The resolution drafted by Costa Rica, Japan, Russia, Slovenia,
Britain and the United States also called on the parties to
"exhaust all means to achieve a peaceful settlement" of their
dispute.
</P>
<P>
The 15 council member states strongly supported the mediation
efforts by the heads of state of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) and urges the OAU to follow up as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
The resolution requested U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
make his good offices in support of a peaceful resolution of the
conflict and consider further recommendations.
</P>
<P>
Annan was requested to provide technical support for the
eventual delimitation and demarcation of the common border between
the two Horn of Africa countries.
</P>
<P>
The border issue centering on a piece of 400 square km land
erupted on May 6 and escalated into a ground and air war on June 5
before both sides agreed to a moratorium.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the OAU summit on June 10, an OAU mediation
group has been established.
</P>
<P>
"There has been for some time in the discussions of the shape
of the eventual peace agreement between Ethiopia and Eritrea, a
border demarcation exercise, and there has been talk of United
Nations involvement in that, but of course we are still far from a
peace agreement in that dispute," U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said
Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
