<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Free Democrats Remain Loyal to Kohl's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Free Democratic Party (FDP)
voted Friday to stay loyal to German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
three-party ruling coalition after the general elections this
September.
</P>
<P>
An overwhelming majority of the 662 delegates present at a FDP
party convention in the eastern German city of Leipzig Friday
voted in favor of a continuation of their center-right coalition
with Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party and its sister
party Christian Social Union (CSU).
</P>
<P>
However, many delegates speaking at the convention criticized
the CDU for blocking faster and more fundamental structural
reforms sought by the FDP in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
They also vowed to be more independent and to sharpen their
profile as a staunch advocate of economic and social reforms.
</P>
<P>
"We want more jobs through tax reform, privatization and the
reduction of state subsidies and bureaucracy," said FDP leader
Wolfgang Gerhardt in an opening speech to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He also set out a five-point program to be pursued by his party
in the coming years, including continued tax and social reforms,
continued efforts to rebuild eastern Germany, a comprehensive
education reform, more liberal immigration regulations, and a
reliable foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
The tiny FDP has been crucial to keeping Kohl in power in the
past 16 years. Without the votes won by the liberal party, Kohl
would not have won the four general elections since 1982.
</P>
<P>
However, at a time when Germany's unemployment is hovering at
record highs, Kohl's coalition have been losing popular support to
the main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD).
</P>
<P>
The SPD is striving for a leftist coalition with the ecologist
Greens party to force Kohl from power on September 27 when the
national vote is due to be held. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
