<HEADLINE> Balkan Military Experts Meeting Ends in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The five-day meeting of military
experts from seven Balkan countries ended here Friday with a joint
communique calling for cooperation in the future.
</P>
<P>
In a joint communique released after the meeting, the military
experts expressed satisfaction over progress achieved to date and
agreed on future cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The military experts also decided to staff officers levels and
create a committee of diplomats and military experts to direct the
multinational peacekeeping force's operations.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which began Monday, was attended by delegates from
Albania, Bulgaria, Greece, Romania, Turkey, Italy, the former
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia (FYROM) and observers from the U.S.
and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
The participants discussed the procedural issues regarding the
establishment of a multinational force with the aim of preventing
conflict and maintaining peace and stability in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
The military experts are expected to meet again in Rome in
September to pave the way for a defense ministers' conference
which will take place in the same month in the FYROM.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministers' conference will discuss issues
concerning the location of the force's headquarters and which
country has the command of the force. 
