<HEADLINE> UN Envoy to Angola Tours W. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Blondin Beye, the United Nations
Special Envoy to Angola, left here for Sao Tome &AMP; Principe, his
first leg of a tour of five western African nations, to enlist
support for the peace process in Angola.
</P>
<P>
During his western African tour which also covers Gabon, Togo,
Cote d'Ivoire and Burkina Faso, Beye will brief leaders of these
countries on the current situation in Angola and seek support for
the U.N. move to overcome the difficulties in the country.
</P>
<P>
Blaise Compaore, President of Burkina Faso and the current
Chairman of the Organization of African Unity (OAU), would be the
key figure for Beye to enlist his support, since Beye wants to
make use of Compaore's influence as the OAU chairman to tackle
the Angolan crisis.
</P>
<P>
This is the second of Beye's African tour within a month for
the Angolan crisis. He had visited Zambia, Namibia and Zimbabwe
before his western African tour earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan peace process hit snags again as the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) put off, as
formerly agreed, to hand over administrations of four sensitive
regions under its control to the government.
</P>
<P>
According to a U.N. Security Council resolution passed
Wednesday, UNITA should hand over the four areas now under its
control, to the government before the June 30 deadline, or face
the punishment of having its bank accounts abroad frozen and its
diamond exports banned.
</P>
<P>
During his two tours of African countries Beye is expected to
ask for these countries' support for the U.N. resolution once the
UNITA fails to fulfill its hand-over of the areas to the
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
