<HEADLINE> Canada's Call-Net, Fonorola Agree to Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Canada's two long-distance phone
companies, Call-Net Enterprises and Fonorola Inc., announced
Friday that they have agreed to merge in a 1.8 billion dollar
(1.2 billion U.S. dollar) deal.
</P>
<P>
The merger will push Call-Net Enterprises up to be Canada's
largest alternative long-distance phone company in the
increasingly competitive market.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Call-Net will pay 67 dollars or 2.68 of its
non-voting B-class shares for each share of the Montreal-based
Fonorola company.
</P>
<P>
"This transaction creates synergies that could not have been
realized by any other combination," Call-Net President Juri Koor
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The deal "will accelerate Call-Net's growth as the leading
alternative long distance telecommunications company in
Canada.... It also advances our efforts to expand in the U.S. and
international market," he said.
</P>
<P>
The combined company would have had over 1.3 billion dollars in
revenues in 1997, and a 16 percent share of Canada's 8.6 billion
dollar market for long distance services.
</P>
<P>
Call-Net, which is based in Toronto, will have a combined
network of more than 23,000 kilometers of fiber route, serving
more than 1.35 million customers in Canada, with connections into
the U.S. and overseas.
</P>
<P>
Over the next two years, Call-Net said it expects to become a
full service telecommunications firm in Canada offering a wide
range of products, including long distance, local, data, Internet
and mobile service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
