<HEADLINE> Lebanese Extend Freed Prisoners Hero's Welcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon Friday extended a hero's
welcome to 55 prisoners released by Israel in a swap between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Lebanese surged as two buses and an ambulance of
the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) carrying the
prisoners moved slowly through the crowds at the Kfar Falous
crossing.
</P>
<P>
The crowds had been waiting for hours at the usually quiet
crossing, which links the Israeli-occupied south Lebanon and the
rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
Relatives of the prisoners were excited to see the return of
their husbands and sons, most of whom have spent at least 10 years
in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
Most of the prisoners are members of the anti-Israeli
resistance groups like Hezbollah, Amal movement and the Communist
Party,
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a so-called security zone covering an area of
1,200 square kilometers in south Lebanon in 1985 with a claimed
aim to protect its northern areas from cross-border attacks by
Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese resistance forces have been fighting to drive the
Israeli troops out of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The crowds chanted anti-Israeli slogans and sang Hezbollah
songs. Some waved flags and banners reading "Freedom returned with
our liberated detainees" and "Our martyrs and prisoners are the
symbols of our struggle and victory."
</P>
<P>
The freed prisoners then received a grand banquet hosted by
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri at his palace in the capital.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the banquet, Hariri praised the prisoners for
their struggle for the "nation's right to live in freedom and
dignity."
</P>
<P>
He also glorified the guerrillas who have died in fightings
against the Israeli occupation of Lebanon's soil.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister noted that the government is determined to
liberate all the Lebanese detainees in the Jewish state through
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
About 150 more Lebanese people are still held by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Friday's release of the prisoners came in an ICRC-mediated swap
deal, which is the biggest in two years between Lebanon and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel set free 60 prisoners. Four of them chose to stay in
homes in the occupied zone and one decided to remain in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel also returned 40 bodies of Lebanese guerrillas,
including that of Hadi Nasrallah, the eldest son of Hezbollah's
leader Sheikh Hassan Nasrallah.
</P>
<P>
In return, Lebanon Thursday handed over the remains of an
Israeli soldier killed in a botched raid in south Lebanon last
September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
