<HEADLINE> Malawi Currency Devalued Considerably </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Malawi's currency has been
devalued considerably with 26.5 Kwacha against one U.S. Dollar
compared with 15 Kwacha against one at the same time of 1997,
according to the Reserve Bank of Malawi.
</P>
<P>
Four years ago the Kwacha was at 2.5 to the Dollar.
</P>
<P>
The unsteady Kwacha has not been backed by an inflation rate
of 20.20 percent, which has made the cost of borrowing from the
banks extremely expensive, the Pan-African News Agency (PANA)
quoted an economist as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said to borrow money from a commercial bank, a client
should be prepared to pay a prime lending rate of 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
PANA did not mention the name of the economist or say when he
made the remarks.
</P>
<P>
Compared to past years, bank managers demanded a prime lending
rate of only 23 percent, said the economist.
</P>
<P>
"Building materials keep going up every week. You just can't
budget for anything," said a borrower who is struggling to build
a new house in Blantyre, southern Malawi.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Commercial Bank of Malawi has successfully
subscribed 24 million shares to its employees and the public, the
bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
