<P>
It was a reaction to a shift in policy from Liberian President
Charles Taylor's regime, the force said in a statement issued at
its headquarters in Monrovia, capital of Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to a program on local television which gave the
impression that the withdrawal was to enable the troops to visit
their families, the force said it could be attributed to two
recent incidents involving the country's security forces and
ECOMOG troops.
</P>
<P>
The two incidents, which took place on June 21 and 22
respectively, included the refusal of Adolphus Taylor, a relation
of the president, to be subjected to a search at the Parker Point
check-point, as well as the attempt by Liberian soldiers to
search an ECOMOG vehicle on a supply mission to troops in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
"Although these two incidents have no direct bearing, they
both represent a shift in policy by the Liberian government in
its relationship with ECOMOG," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said that during the Parker Point incident, an ECOMOG
soldier was dragged to the presidential villa and maltreated in
the presence of the director of the State Security Service (SSS)
in violation of the spirit of the status of forces agreement
signed with ECOWAS.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS, namely the Economic Community of West African States,
sent ECOMOG to Liberia in 1990 to help bring to an end the bloody
civil war in that country. The force did it and created
conditions for Taylor to win last year's election to become the
post-war president.
</P>
<P>
"The (ECOMOG) high command views these acts as diametrically
opposed and incompatible with the spirit and letter of the
agreement and the previously existing cordial working
relationship between ECOMOG and the government," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The attempt to attribute the withdrawal to welfare matters was
misleading as the force was in the habit of granting leave to
troops to attend to their families without compromising its
responsibility, it noted.
</P>
<P>
It has been reported repeatedly that Taylor does not like
ECOMOG and has asked the force to leave his country.
</P>
<P>
It is also reported that ECOMOG is considering to move its
headquarters from Monrovia to Freetown, capital of neighboring
Sierra Leone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
