<HEADLINE> Super Eagles Eager to Win for Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Super Eagles from Nigeria are
thirsty for a second round victory over Denmark not only for
themselves but also for the African soccer.
</P>
<P>
The point was emphasized through the words of striker Victor Ikpeba
after they qualified for the last 16 by beating Bulgaria in their
second game.
</P>
<P>
Ikpeba said: "It was a victory for the team. It is also a victory
for the African soccer."
</P>
<P>
Of the five African nations here, Nigeria are the only one that has
survived the grilling of the first round,
</P>
<P>
But the Super Eagles want to avoid the disaster in 1994 when they
were shot down by the eventual runners-up Italians.
</P>
<P>
The best record for an African team was registered by Cameroon who
reached the quarterfinals in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The only setback for the Nigerian camp is the injury of striker
Daniel Amokachi, the 1994 star who will miss the match.
</P>
<P>
But coach Bora Milutinovic has rested their key players in the last
group match against Paraguay, paying the price of a 3-1 loss which did
not affect their qualification.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, an overaged Denmark would still depend on the
skills of Laudrup brothers.
</P>
<P>
The younger Brian said: "This is perhaps our chance -- a chance we
may not have had against teams like for example Germany, the
Netherlands or Yugoslavia. That is why we think that something big is
in the making."
</P>
<P>
Denmark will also trying to surmount the barrier of second round as
they have never gone beyond.
</P>
<P>
Goalkeeper Peter Schmeichel, who plays for Manchester United, is
the final defence against the Nigerian strikers and he would
definitely not want to let his first and probably last World Cup ends
so early. 
</P>
</TEXT>
