<HEADLINE> Arabs Urged to Open Markets to Somali Livestock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the Arab League
(AL) Saturday called on Arab countries to reopen their markets to
Somali livestock, the only source of income to the majority of the
war-ravaged Somalis.
</P>
<P>
Abdallah Adam, the advisor to the AL secretary general, said
the his organization has received reports from various United
Nations organizations saying that Somali livestock is free from
diseases that prevent the export.
</P>
<P>
It is known that the U.N. Development Program, the World Health
Organization and the Food and Agriculture Organization have sent
such reports to the 22-member Arab group.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has a huge livestock - about 80 million heads of cattle
in addition to some 70 million others - that are untamed and could
be widely used by Arab countries, Adam said.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. delegation visited Somalia to verify the fact that
Somali livestock did not catch any diseases from Kenya and wrote a
report after four months of research, proving that there are no
diseases among animals in Somalia, Adam added.
</P>
<P>
The Arab official called on the private sector and importers in
Arab countries to make use of such "enormous and cheap animal
livestock" in the Horn of African state.
</P>
<P>
Somalia has been hit hard by factional wars since the ouster of
late President Mohamed Siad Barre in 1991. More than 300,000 people
have died in the war and concurrent famine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
