<HEADLINE> Tanzania Carvers Stops Using Ebony for Wood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania Carvers'
Association (TCA) has stopped using the ebony tree to make
carvings for the sake of protecting the endangered species.
</P>
<P>
The association is encouraging its 1,400 members to use other
trees for wood carvings, which are tourist souvenirs attractive
to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The move has been in response to the government call, said the
TCA secretary general, Raymond Likajuma, who expressed concern
that the trees may soon perish if they are not properly
protected.
</P>
<P>
"Ebony trees, available in Morogoro and Coast regions, have
been felled indiscriminately," the Saturday's Guardian quoted
Likajum as saying recently.
</P>
<P>
Likajuma said that the association is doing its best to
persuade its members to try other tree varieties which are able
to produce quality carvings as well. He urged the carvers to
change with the tide of time instead of sticking to traditional
ways.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, he said, some carvers doubted whether other
types of trees are suitable for the production of quality
carvings.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the experience at an art institute in
Bagamoyo in north Dar es Salaam has proved that other types of
trees serve as good materials as ebony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
