<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Dumps June 12, Supports New Election in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has made it
clear that it wants a new election to be held in Nigeria, instead
of installing Moshood Abiola, the presumed winner of the June 12,
1993 election, as the president.
</P>
<P>
Tony Lloyd, the British Deputy Foreign Minister made this
known while addressing newsmen in Lagos Friday night before
winding up his one-day visit to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd arrived in Nigeria Thursday night as a special envoy of
the British Prime Minister Tony Blair and the EU. His mission is
to express the EU's concern with Nigeria's transition to civil
rule program, now at a cross with the sudden death of late
military leader, General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd held a closed-door talk with Nigeria's new leader,
General Abdulsalam Abubakar, in the federal capital Abuja Friday.
He described the talk as "constructive."
</P>
<P>
He said he welcomed the release of 17 political detainees by
Abubakar just before his arrival and called for the early
resolution of the case of Moshood Abiola, who has been in
detention for five years.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to the call of pro-democracy groups in Nigeria that
Abiola should be given his mandate as winner of the June 12, 1993
election, Lloyd said that the feeling of the international
community, especially of the EU, is that a new election should be
held.
</P>
<P>
"What we insisted on is a proper election. What we want for
the people of Nigeria is a transparent election progress," he
told the press.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd, who is a member of the parliament, said that in
Britain, the parliament does not sit for more than five years,
meaning that Abiola's mandate is no longer relevant.
</P>
<P>
As close and traditional friends of the Nigerian people,
Britain and the EU are ready to support Nigeria's transition to
democracy process, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, Lloyd made it clear that before Nigeria could effect
a genuine transition, EU will not lift its sanctions against the
west African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
