<HEADLINE> Many Mozambican Women Not to Vote: Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Many Mozambican women might not
vote in the coming local elections, the pro-government newspaper,
Noticias, said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to the polls made by the newspaper, a large number
of women in the capital city of Maputo still don't know there
will be local elections just three days before the event.
</P>
<P>
Some women who do know there will be elections, however, do
not know when the local elections take place and who are the
candidates, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it expected that many Mozambican women might not
vote in the elections scheduled on June 30.
</P>
<P>
The paper also reported that the campaign starting on June 15
for the posts of the mayors and members of the hall in 33 cities
and towns ended peacefully at zero hour.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Mozambique Liberation Front Party (Frelimo), the
Labor Party and 11 mass organizations took part in the election
campaign, the report said. But the biggest opposition party, the
Mozambican National Resistance (Renamo) and other 16 oppositon
parties did not participate in the running.
</P>
<P>
In some provinces, the supporters of the rivaling parties
threw words and stones at each other, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Some supporters for the elections have been beaten by Renamo
members in the provinces of Tete, Manica and Sofala, but with no
serious results.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government is taking measures to ensure order
and security in every poll posts on June 30, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
