<HEADLINE> Mugabe Urges Britain to Help Zimbabwe With Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Saturday urged Britain to help Zimbabwe with its land reform.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the British government is now
accepting its moral obligation on the need to assist Zimbabwe
implement its controversial land acquisition program.
</P>
<P>
But Mugabe said despite the new signs of acceptance, the
British were still however, insisting that the land
redistribution program be done in a way that would alleviate
poverty in this southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who also is the First Secretary of the ruling Zimbabwe
African National Union (Patriotic Front) (ZANU-PF), said this
when he addressed the ruling party's annual national consultative
assembly at ZANU-PF headquarters in Harare.
</P>
<P>
Although there were differences within the government on how
land for redistribution would be acquired, there was need for a
speedy program to resettle millions of peasants squashed in
barren and sandy communal areas, the Zimbabwe News Agency quoted
the president as saying.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recent move by thousands of Svosve and
Nyamandlovu villagers who invaded white-owned commercial farms,
Mugabe said people were getting more impatient and tired of
promises as they only enjoy political and not economic
independence.
</P>
<P>
President Mugabe assured thousands of villagers in the Svosve
and Nyamandlovu and all other land-hungry peasants, that land
would soon be made available for their resettlement with the
government already having made available 104 farms for that
purpose.
</P>
<P>
He pleaded with the villagers to go back to their homesteads
and wait for an organized resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
The president also spoke strongly on the "ugly phenomenon of
factionalism" which he said still haunted the party, splitting
its people into "antagonistic" groups that worked against
collective goals enunciated in its policies and decisions.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from the problem of weakening cohesion, the party's
organizational structures have become enervated, especially in
urban areas where most of these anti-party forces are active," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
