<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Thai Foreign Minister Surin
Pitsuwan met Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun Sen here Saturday
to discuss forthcoming elections in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Arriving here in the afternoon and entering into talks with Hun
Sen at the Premier Office, Surin's party included Indonesian and
Philippine Ambassadors to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The three came to brief on the views expressed by the Friends
of Cambodia grouping and the "Troika" of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
The "Troika," of Thailand, Indonesia and the Philippines,
discussed the Cambodian Elections in Bangkok on June 20.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from his meeting with Hun Sen and before flying home,
Surin told reporters that their talks were "successful" and he was
"very satisfied" with the election process.
</P>
<P>
"We think all the preparations have been going well and last
few days of the campaign have been very smoothly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that his party has no intention to interfere Cambodia's
internal affairs he said: "we only want to help with the Cambodian
government and so far we think we have cooperated very well."
</P>
<P>
On his part, Hun Sen reportedly expressed his willingness to
welcome observers from international non-government organizations
(NGO) and said the more NGO observers, the better.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Hun Sen's remarks, Surin said NGO observers would
help the world to know that everything here was in good order, and
then help bring in support for Cambodia's reconstruction efforts.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Thai foreign minister raised concerns
about continued extra-judicial killings in Cambodia. However, Hun
Sen denied there were political murders relating to the elections.
</P>
<P>
About voter registration for Cambodian refugees in Thailand,
Hun Sen said it should be decided by the National Election
Committee, as it is beyond the government's authority.
</P>
<P>
About 55,000 Cambodian refugees are still on the Thai soil.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Hun Sen made it clear to his quests that Cambodia
would prepare to join the ASEAN at any time.
</P>
<P>
Before Surin and his party's arrival here, they flew to Siem
Reap and met King Norodom Sihanouk. He described the meeting with
the King also as "very successful." 
</P>
