<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Investigating Nazi Behavior of German Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- German police said Saturday they are
investigating alleged Nazi behavior by three German soldiers while
watching a television broadcast of a World Cup football match.
</P>
<P>
As reported by eyewitnesses, a group of German soldiers made
Nazi salute when the German national anthem was played ahead of
last Thursday's World Cup match between Germany and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Nazi salute is constitutionally forbidden in Germany.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers have also been seen, at a cafe in the southern
German city of Regensburg, wearing T-shirts printed with the
slogan: "We march into France in 1998."
</P>
<P>
Three soldiers based near the city have been detained in
connection with the incident.
</P>
<P>
German army officials said Saturday they were shocked by the
new incident and would take harsh disciplinary measures against
the soldiers if their behavior was confirmed.
</P>
<P>
The German military was hit by a series of neo-Nazi scandals
last years with incidents ranging from soldiers making Nazi
salute, chanting Nazi slogans to conducting mock execution of Jews.
</P>
<P>
The scandals also prompted the German parliament to launch a
special investigation into the general morale of the German army
earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
