<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guilin Flood Waters Recede </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Flood waters have receded and daily
life returned to normal today under clear skies and sunshine in
Guilin, a scenic city in southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Some 24 pleasure boats carrying 494 foreign tourists and nearly
2,000 local residents sailed to Yangshuo County along the Lijiang
River, one of the region's most popular tourist attractions, at
10:00 this morning.
</P>
<P>
While Guilin has reeled under the heaviest flooding in 80 years
in recent days, reports from the regional water resources bureau
indicate that the water level had dropped to 144.57 meters by
14:00 (local time) today. Water levels continue to fall by some
eight cm./hour below the normal level set at 145 meters.
</P>
<P>
The city's power generation, water supply, transportation and
telecommunications sectors had resumed normal by Thursday, with
shops, restaurants and free markets opening on Saturday. Schools
and most enterprises are also operating normally.
</P>
<P>
Separate reports indicate that torrential rains continued to
ravage central China's Hunan Province, with water levels in
Changsha City, Wangcheng County and several other areas surpassing
record highs set in 1994.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
