<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference Promotes Scientific Innovation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Guangzhao, vice-chairman of
the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC),
today urged sponsors of the Xiangshan Science Conference which is
celebrating its fifth anniversary to provide greater latitude for
exchanges and discussions of new scientific ideas.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the conference's 100th symposium, Zhou said
that "China should avoid simply following scientific innovations
introduced in other countries, but instead should score
achievements which glorify the scientific history of human beings."
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists should explore interesting topics from the
frontiers of science and carry out creative studies, said Zhou,
adding that redundant studies of short-term projects should be
reduced, while rewarding long-term studies in the basic sciences
should be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
"Individuals lacking creative ideas can never become true
scientists", and "releasing the creativity of scientists will be
the key to promoting the research and development of the basic
sciences in China," said Zhou.
</P>
<P>
He expressed an expectation that the conference will alter the
traditional conceptual style of China's scientific community by
encouraging young scientists to challenge the authoritarianism of
their older peers and enhance the openness of discussions and
debate.
</P>
<P>
The conference carrying the theme "promoting innovation" was
initiated in 1993 by the former State Science and Technology
Commission and the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The 99-odd symposia held to date have promoted comprehensive
studies of various subjects and helped scientists in differing
gain a greater understanding of other areas.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing two-day symposium, which opened in Beijing today,
has attracted the participation of more than 90 Chinese
scientists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
