<HEADLINE> Major News Items In U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Saturday:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton received his official welcome to China
this morning in the vast expanse of Tiananmen Square, ignoring
criticism at home as he strolled with President Jiang Zemin along
a red carpet past rows of People's Liberation Army troops standing
stiffly at attention.
</P>
<P>
-- Supporters of the Good Friday peace agreement appeared to
be heading toward clear majority control of the new Northern
Ireland Assembly Friday.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Serbian forces, planes and heavy weapons were massing for
large-scale attacks to retake parts of Kosovo held by ethnic
Albanian rebels and to reopen roads blocked by the separatists for
weeks.
</P>
<P>
-- A former member of a Japanese military unit that conducted
experiments on prisoners during World War II was kept from
entering the United States this week, under a law barring war
criminals, even though he was coming in an effort to press Japan
to apologize and pay reparations to its war victims. 
</P>
