<HEADLINE> Chinese Rural Medical Foundation Enters Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Rural Medical Relief
Foundation established by central China's Hunan Province will
provide free treatment for 200,000 rural tuberculosis patients.
</P>
<P>
In early 1997, the province decided to establish the
foundation, which became the first organization of its kind
covering medical services for Chinese farmers.
</P>
<P>
The foundation has accumulated funds totalling 15 million yuan
(1.8 million US dollars) which are mainly used to cover the
expenses of poverty-stricken farmers suffering from tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
"Patients approved by the county epidemic prevention center
enjoy free medical treatment," according to a foundation official.
</P>
<P>
Farmers account for the bulk of Hunan's over 500,000
tuberculosis patients.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to bring tuberculosis under control by the
year 2000.  
</P>
