<HEADLINE> Flood Conditions Deteriorate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The heaviest flooding in China
since 1949 was recorded today on the Xijiang River, a tributary of
the Pearl River in South China, according to a report issued by
the State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that the Yangtze, the longest river in
China, has witnessed constantly rising water levels resulting from
heavy rainfall since mid-June.
</P>
<P>
Dongting and Boyang lakes, two of the largest lakes on the
Yangtze, are also witnessing increasingly dangerous conditions,
with record water levels continuing to rise.
</P>
<P>
The first heavy flooding in northeast China was reported today
along the Nenjiang River.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities in
south China have suffered from heavy flooding that has caused
substantial losses of human life and property. The most severe
flooding has hit Fujian, Jiangxi, Hunan and Guangdong provinces,
and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
