<HEADLINE> China Approves Eastern Port Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The port of Zhapu in China's
Zhejiang Province plans to build three new offshore berths and
inland supporting facilities in the next two years, a deal that
has been approved by the State Development Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
A 15,000-dwt berth for sundry goods, a 15,000-dwt multi-purpose
berth, and a 20,000-dwt coal berth have been listed on the port's
second-phase expansion project, which will cost 730 million yuan
(87.95 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Zhapu, which is near Shanghai, has 70 km of coastline with a
depth of 10 to 15 m, and is generally considered a good deep-water
port. It now has 7 berths and a combined cargo handling capacity
of 15 million tons annually. Last year, it handled seven million
tons of cargo, the second largest amount among the four ports in
Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
Zhapu is expected to have a total cargo handling capacity of 30
million tons by the year 2000 and 50 million tons by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The port has had customs offices, frontier inspection offices,
commodity checks, quarantine monitors, and other services since it
was approved by the State Council in 1996 as a first-class open
port. 
</P>
</TEXT>
