<HEADLINE> Flood Waters Inundate China's Porcelain Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Torrential rain over the past few
days have inundated over 70 percent of urban Jingdezhen, known as
the porcelain capital of China in east China's Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Flood water levels reaching depths of nine meters covered some
26-odd city streets on Friday. Flooding also disrupted traffic and
telecommunications, as well as the city's water and electricity
supply. Reports indicate that flood waters stranded more than
80,000 residents in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Flooding hit some 20-odd towns and villages in suburban areas
forcing more than 40,000 local residents to find temporary
shelters. The heaviest flooding in the city's history has caused
record property losses, according to local sources.
</P>
<P>
Relief efforts are continuing and no deaths have been
reported.
</P>
<P>
Other reports indicate that this year's third flood peak along
the Ganjiang River has passed Nanchang, capital of Jiangxi
Province. However, the water level remains at 1.55 meters above
warning level.  
</P>
</TEXT>
