<HEADLINE> Feature: Hong Kong - One of Safest Cities in World (1) By Feng Xiuju </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Cho has been keeping order by
the door at several banks in Hong Kong for a total of 20 years,
but has never felt so secure as it is now.
</P>
<P>
"Some banks have been equipped with bulletproof glass so that
people's safety can be guaranteed," said the 63-year-old Cho, who
is now working in a branch of the Bank of China.
</P>
<P>
Several years ago, however, his friend witnessed right here a
bank robbery involving pistols.
</P>
<P>
"It was too terrible to say," recalled Cho who previously
served as a guard in the Hong Kong and Shanghai Bank and the
Standard Chartered Bank.
</P>
<P>
"Nowadays I seldom hear such kind of robbery cases, especially
after Hong Kong returned to China last July," Cho said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
His words are backed up by facts. A 73 percent drop was
scored in the number of bank robberies in 1997 from the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's safety is not merely reflected in the banking
sector. Last year saw a marked decrease in burglaries for four
years in a row, down by 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that Hong Kong's overall crime rate in
1996, one year before its return to China, was the lowest in 15
years and the downward trend continued in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Compared with 1996, the overall crime rate and violent crime
rate dropped by 17.3 percent and 12.4 percent respectively, the
lowest in 24 years.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of this year, these two kinds of crime
rates recorded further decreases of 2.4 percent and 12 percent
respectively compared with the corresponding period of last year,
Ng Ching-kwok, senior assistant commissioner of police said.
</P>
<P>
"Our detection rate of 51.4 percent compares favorably with
other densely populated cities worldwide," he told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the year of 1997, the police force continued its
determined enforcement action against drug trafficking and drug
abuse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
