<HEADLINE> Zidane-less France to Find Way Past Paraguayans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LENS, June 27 (Xinhua) -- France, without playmaker Zinedine
Zidane, will have to find a way past in-form Paraguay here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A flare-up of temper in a group game led to Juventus midfielder
Zidane being sent off in their group game against Saudi Arabia and
subsequent two-game ban.
</P>
<P>
Coach Aime Jacquet had to make eight changes in starting line-up
against Denmark, including Youri Djorkaeff shouldering the
responsibility of feeding strikers like David Trezeguet and instant
hero Christophe Dugarry who scored in their opening game.
</P>
<P>
Dugarry is doubtful for Sunday's game after being injured against
Saudi Arabia but captain Didier Deschamp and Emmanuel Petit, yellow
carded in the first round, now can play without worrying about
suspension as the second round starts afresh.
</P>
<P>
The game against the Danes reflected France's remarkable depth in
bench talents and constantly deafening vocal support from local fans
is also a plus that could not be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
Although the performances in the three games proved that doubters
of lack of attacking power were wrong, coach Aimer Jacquet cautioned
that Paraguay are not minnows.
</P>
<P>
"We can't take the game lightly. We have to prepare well. During
their games the Paraguayans have gronw in stature and really
progressed," Jacquet said.
</P>
<P>
He added, "They are a passionate team, very compact and they work
hard to retieve possession of the ball."
</P>
<P>
But the Frenchmen should be wary of the attacking power unleashed
by midfielder Jose Cardozo and Miguel Benitez of Spanish club
Espanyol.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure of French attacks, Paraguyan goalkeeper Jose
Luis Chilavert will not have an easy day.
</P>
<P>
But if necessary, "The Bulldog" is likely to call upon his scoring
skill, which has brought five goals for the Paraguayan eleven. 
</P>
