<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: New Airport, Pride of Hong Kong, Says Wong (1) by Wang Qun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- "Hong Kong's new international
airport at Chek Lap Kok ranks among the world's most majestic
projects and its opening on July 6 will be a landmark in the
development of Hong Kong," said Wong Po-yan, chairman of the Hong
Kong Airport Authority (AA).
</P>
<P>
Within less than nine years, a world-class new airport took
shape at the reclaimed land off the northern coast of Lantau
Island, and was supported by nine related projects, including
roads and bridges, an airport railway, a tunnel and a new town,
Wong told Xinhua in an interview.
</P>
<P>
The whole set of projects, known as the Airport Core Program,
cost a total of 155.3 billion HK dollars (19.9 billion
U.S. dollars), which will be the largest infrastructure
development project in Hong Kong's history.
</P>
<P>
With just ten days left before the historic opening of the new
airport, the AA is busy conducting the last-minute operational
trials and coordinating the challenging relocation of airport from
the downtown Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok, 25 kilometers west of Hong
Kong's central business district.
</P>
<P>
With some 30 years of experience behind him in public service,
the 75-year-old Wong is very proud of having the grand project
finished within budget and on schedule.
</P>
<P>
"This clearly demonstrated that Hong Kong kept its promises,
and also had the financial capability to do what it wanted to do,"
he stressed, comparing the new airport with quite a few
infrastructure projects in other parts of Asia which had to be
suspended due to the regional financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"The people of Hong Kong will feel a great source of pride in
the wonderful facility which creates a lot of superlatives over
the world," Wong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: New Airport, Pride of Hong Kong, Says Wong (2) by Wang Qun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wong has been involved in the project from the very beginning.
Before taking the chair of the Airport Authority, a full
government-owned body in charge of building and running the new
airport, Wong was chairman of the Airport Consultative Committee
which advised the government on the new airport.
</P>
<P>
The new airport's Y-shaped terminal, with a floor area nine
times as large as that at Kai Tak, is the world's largest airport
terminal and indoor public place, Wong pointed out, adding that
everyone should find its panoramic views and spaciousness
impressive.
</P>
<P>
Departing passengers should take less than three minutes to
check in at nearly 300 desks. From each of these desks, luggage
will move smoothly on its way through a sophisticated baggage
handling and screening system. For arrivals, with 12 reclaim
carousels handling almost 20,000 pieces of luggage an hour,
passengers will be able to retrieve their baggage quickly.
</P>
<P>
The new airport also boasts of the most state-of-the-art air
traffic control system, a north runway with the highest safety
grade, the largest air cargo handling facility and even a kitchen
capable of providing 80,000 meals daily for passengers, Wong
continued.
</P>
<P>
The list could still go on. Actually thousands of Hong Kong
residents have seen for themselves what a great achievement the
new airport has been. Anxious to taste the new airport, they
participated in "the New Airport Experience", an AA program of
public open days to familiarize Hong Kong people with their new
airport.
</P>
<P>
He said, operating around the clock, the new airport is able to
handle up to 35 million passengers or 1.2 times of that in Kai
Tak, and 3 million tons of cargo or 2 times of that in Kai Tak, in
its first 12 months of operation while the ultimate capacity will
reach 87 million passengers and 9 million tons of cargo per year.
</P>
<P>
Built to meet the aviation demands of Hong Kong, southern China
and the broader Asia-Pacific region for at least 50 years, the new
airport will bring overall economic benefits to Hong Kong,
strengthening the city's status as an Asian aviation, tourism,
trade and financial center in the long term, Wong noted.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, following the closure of Kai Tak, some
380,000 Kowloon City residents living under its flight path will
obviously escape the noise of aircraft, while additional land will
be made available for residential and commercial developments in
the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
