<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Urges Judicial Officials to be Impartial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
Saturday called on the country's judicial officials to be
impartial and free from any political influence.
</P>
<P>
"Judges should be impartial in all ways and must not side with
any specific trend, group and tendency," Khatami said at a
nationwide gathering of judiciary officials, according to the
Iranian official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a judge is not subordinate to the command of any
individual and no superior official can tell him what to do and
not to do.
</P>
<P>
The criterion in Islamic judicial system is restoration of
rights and nothing should prevent such a grave task, Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president made the remarks after the moderate
faction in Iran accused the pro-conservative judiciary of putting
Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi on an open trial for
political purpose aimed at weakening Khatami's government.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi's case aroused a serious factional struggle between
the moderates and conservatives. The judiciary is expected to
announce a final rule on Karbaschi next month.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said that Islam does not favor scrutinizing in order to
find faults, rather, the most important principle in Islam is the
principle of acquittal. He warned that any violation of this
principle will be dealt with severely.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that no power is authorized to force a judge to
issue a certain verdict and judges should function in total
freedom, stressing the need to avoid forced extraction of
confession and the unpleasant methods.
</P>
<P>
Any citizen in the country is entitled to certain rights and
the Islamic system is responsible to guarantee those rights,
Khatami said, adding that the president is responsible for the
execution of the constitution and all should coordinate their
actions within this framework.
</P>
<P>
A two-day nationwide gathering of the judiciary officials
opened here Saturday morning to debate issues related to
supervisory commissions of the judiciary, practical boundaries of
judiciary, Islamic human rights, prison affairs, security and
correctional measures and women's issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
