<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Meets With U.N. Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The special envoy of the United
Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan on Saturday delivered a
personal letter of the world body chief to Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina on the tension in South Asia following the nuclear tests by
India and Pakistan last month.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief was concerned about the nuclear tests carried
out by India and Pakistan, Alvaro De Soto, U.N. assistant
secretary general for political affairs, told Hasina at a meeting
Saturday morning, a spokesman of the prime minister told a news
briefing.
</P>
<P>
Annan had conveyed the same concern to the respective
countries, and suggested initiation of dialog between India and
Pakistan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hasina welcomed the envoy and thanked the secretary general for
the message.
</P>
<P>
On her recent visits to India and Pakistan, Hasina said they
were aimed at better appreciation of the two countries'
constraints and concern, avoiding arms race in the region, urging
the two countries to resolve all outstanding issues through dialog
and peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister said that she had not offered
mediation between her country's two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Calling for a tension- and (nuclear) weapon-free world, she
said peace was essential for development and welfare of the people
of the region.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad soon after
his arrival Friday afternoon, the U.N. envoy said that he would
discuss (with the prime minister) the possibility of Annan's
planned visit to the region.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of my mission is not to mediate, but to hand over
the messages (of Annan) to the leaders of Bangladesh and
Pakistan," said Soto, who is scheduled to fly to Karachi,
Pakistan, Saturday evening after his one-day Bangladesh visit.
</P>
<P>
India is against outside involvement in resolving its disputes
with Pakistan, while the latter favors the U.N. or any third party
to help in this regard.
</P>
<P>
India would refuse to receive the U.N. envoy, Indian Foreign
Ministry spokesman Sunil Lal said Thursday, reports reaching here
said. "They are talking about Indo-Pakistan matters and Kashimir.
You know our stand," he was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
