<HEADLINE> ASEAN Urges Japan to Stop Yen Slide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Rodolfo Severino, secretary general
of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), Friday
called on Japan to work with the group of seven industrialized
countries to arrest the slide of the yen.
</P>
<P>
Severino, who made the call at the annual ASEAN-Japan forum
held in Hanoi, also asked for an early implementation of the 16
trillion yen (about 120 billion U.S. dollars) package that the
Japanese government had put together to stimulate Japan's economy,
the English "Vietnam News" reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, which was attended by the deputy foreign
ministers of Japan and the ASEAN members, Severino said that the
weakness of the Japanese currency was creating a "dangerous"
situation for Southeast Asia and the whole world as well.
</P>
<P>
The weak yen contributes to the shrinking of Japan's demand for
ASEAN exports and lowers the value of Japanese investments and
assistance to the region in terms of dollar, he added.
</P>
<P>
Severino also stressed that it was necessary to pull ASEAN out
of the economic difficulties arising from the regional financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
A Japanese senior official who attended the forum reiterated
his country's commitment to extend various forms of assistance to
Asian countries amounting to 42 billion dollars and a "solidarity
fund" of 20 million dollars specifically for manpower development,
poverty alleviation and regional projects in ASEAN, said the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
