<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Devalues Rupee by 4.2 Pct to Shore Up Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Saturday devalued
its currency of rupee by 4.2 percent as part of an emergency
package to shore up the country's foreign reserves following its
nuclear tests in late May.
</P>
<P>
The State Bank of Pakistan (SBP) said in a statement that the
new rate of 46.0000/46.4600 rupees against one U.S. dollar would
replace the official 44.0500/44.4905 official rate in force since
March 24 with immediate effect, said reports from Karachi,
Pakistan's southern port city.
</P>
<P>
The move was seen as another part of efforts to shore up the
country's foreign exchange deposits in the wake of sanctions
imposed by major western powers for Pakistan's nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has already frozen foreign accounts in the
country to prevent any run on foreign exchange deposits in light
of its dwindling reserves.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's foreign exchange reserves fell to about 1.5 billion
dollars on June 20 from about 1.6 billion dollars a week earlier,
the central bank said on Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
