<HEADLINE> Italy's Albertini Says Norway Strong in Header </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MARSEILLE, France, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Italy's Demetrio Albertini
said the biggest threat from Norway in their second-round clash was
their headers.
</P>
<P>
"Norway is a better team when it comes to headers," the AC Milan
midfielder said on Friday. "We're going to have to try to win the
battle in the midfield, and recover a maximum number of balls."
</P>
<P>
Italy will face Norway in the Stade Velodrome here later on
Saturday. The winners will enter the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
Albertini said his team would rely on the experience of players who
had honned their skills in the professional leagues.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Professional players should systematically be confident.
This concentration is in fact the most important thing to have in a
World Cup, and you have to maintain it."
</P>
<P>
Italian captain Paolo Maldini said they would take advantage of
tactics to make up for the weakness in height.
</P>
<P>
"The Norwegian players are very athletic very strong, and overall
taller than us," he said. "We also have some big players, but we play
differently to them. It will be hard to find any openings against
Norway."
</P>
<P>
He said both teams had improved since last edition in the United
States in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"The difference between Norway in 1998 and in 1994 is that Norway
have a different style of play, but the same goes for Italy," said
Maldini, who turned 30 on Friday. 
</P>
