<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Urges COMESA to Fully Liberalize Trade, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has urged
the Common Market of Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) to
liberalize trade and agriculture completely.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the COMESA's fifth Council of Ministers meeting
starting Friday in Kinshasa, capital of the Democratic Republic
of Congo, Zambian Minister of Commerce, Trade and Industry Enock
Kavindele said that the COMESA members should adhere to the
regional body's timetable for the reduction of tariffs and
complete elimination of non-tariff barriers.
</P>
<P>
COMESA, originating from Preferential Trade Area for Eastern
and Southern Africa in 1994, aims to achieve a free trade area by
the year 2000 and a customs union as well as free movement of
finance, capital and people in the region, the Times of Zambia
newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kavindele, also Chairman of the Council of Ministers, said
that it is possible to attain free trade in agricultural products
and inputs on January 1, 1999, adding that there will be minimal
losses in revenue when agricultural trade is fully liberalized.
</P>
<P>
Given the related agricultural seasons in the region, said the
Zambian minister, member states should strive to eliminate
cross-border informal trade in agricultural products and expand
market as well as enhance food security in the region.
</P>
<P>
Kavindele stressed that COMESA has reached a critical point in
its history when it is needed to move the region to higher level
of economic cooperation and integration.
</P>
<P>
Industrial cooperation is key to regional integration, he
said, calling on the members to agree to have COMESA become a
free trade area by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"We must, therefore, continue to press on even with greater
determination and commitment if we want to harvest the full
benefits of integration," said Kavindele.
</P>
<P>
The fifth Council of Ministers meeting attracted about 300
delegates from 19 member countries and it will consider, among
other things, reports of various COMESA committees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
