<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Rand in Free Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's currency, the
Rand has gone into a free fall, despite unprecedented support
from the Bank of England and the United States Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
The Rand went into free fall Thursday night, hitting 5.95
against the U.S. Dollar in late trade.
</P>
<P>
Reports from New York dealers that the two big central banks
had bought Rand for Dollars surprised analysts, who said it was
the first time that South Africa had enlisted major powers'
support for the currency, The Citizen daily said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The mauling of the Rand by speculators has underlined the lack
of confidence in the economy and raised the chances that interest
rates will be hiked again, practically killing any chance of
reasonable growth this year.
</P>
<P>
The repo rate, at which the Reserve Bank lends to commercial
banks, had soared to a 13-year high of 24 percent on Monday, but
had been allowed to relax over the week as the semblance of
stability returned.
</P>
<P>
The South African currency has fallen 43 cents or nine percent
since Thursday morning, and in just over a month it has slipped
from 5.080.
</P>
<P>
The Rand traded at 9.8117 against the British Pound, losing
more than 15 percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
Friday's slide came after a firm increase in the repo rate to
18.31 percent from 17.34 percent, which initially seemed to
support the Rand.
</P>
<P>
But fresh waves of selling saw the currency fall steadily
until, dealers said, big central banks came in to support. The
beleaguered currency took some strength from the intervention but
then it fell again.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank intervened heavily to support the Rand in
May, employing 26 billion Rand (4.58 billion U.S. Dollars) to
support the currency in the early stages of an emerging market
assault.
</P>
<P>
But analysts believe that the authorities don't have enough
foreign reserves to intervene again.
</P>
<P>
Economists reckon the central bank should allow the Rand to
slip rather than chance a prolonged period of high interest
rates, which would stifle the fragile economy into full blown
recession. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
