<HEADLINE> Religious Freedom in China Is Protected by Constitution: Jiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua)-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin today
emphasized that the religious freedom in Tibet, as in the other
parts of China, is protected by the country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks while addressing a press conference
following his talks with visiting US president Clinton here today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that he is an atheist as president of the People's
Republic of China and as a Communist Party member.
</P>
<P>
"But this will by no means prevent me from respecting the
religious freedom in Tibet," Jiang told some 300 reporters
present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
