<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Not to Release Pledged Aid to Zambia: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Germany will not release its aid
to Zambia as it pledged until Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM) is privatized, German Ambassador to Zambia has said.
</P>
<P>
It will be economically imprudent if the assistance is
released before the privatization process of ZCCM is completed,
the Zambia Daily Mail Saturday quoted Helmuth Schroeder as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said that the money ZCCM is losing equals the
amount of the aid the donor community pledged to give Zambia and
that if it is released, it will have no impact on its economy and
serve no purpose because all of it will go to bailing out the
ailing ZCCM.
</P>
<P>
While it's the Zambian government's decision to sell the
mines, the donor community largely remains concerned at the slow
pace in privatizing the mines, Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
He underlined the importance of the mining sector to Zambian
economy, saying if there is an adverse effect on it, the rest of
its economy will suffer.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said that the German government does not agree
to the reasons given by the Zambian government on the failure of
the talks with the Kafue Consortium.
</P>
<P>
Zambia discontinued the negotiations last April with Kafue
Consortium on the sale of Nchanga and Nkana mines, which make up
65 percent of the ZCCM assets, over disagreement on the prices of
the two mines.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, two other foreign mining companies pulled out, citing
falling international copper prices as the main reason for their
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the donors pledged Zambia an aid of 530 million
U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Because of the falling copper prices and outdated equipment,
lack of investment and mismanagement, annual copper output of the
southern African country has decreased gradually to about 300,000
tons in recent years from peak 750,000 tons in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
To attract foreign investment, advanced technology and
management to revive the stagnating copper production, Zambia has
invited foreign tenders for the ZCCM mines and assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
