<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President to Visit N. Cyprus in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Amid the new wave of tension
between Greece and Turkey, Turkish President Suleyman Demirel is
due to visit northern Cyprus next month to show Ankara's support
for Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Demirel's visit scheduled for July 20 is to mark the anniversary
of Turkey's military intervention in Cyprus 24 years ago, the
English-language newspaper Daily News reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On July 20, 1974, Turkish troops landed and took over the
northern third of Cyprus in the wake of an abortive coup by Greek
Cypriot army officers who attempted to seek union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Cyprus, Demirel is expected to meet with
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas on the latest developments on
the long-divided island, the paper quoted unnamed diplomats as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish president's trip to northern Cyprus is believed to
be a response to his Greek counterpart Costis Stephanopoulos'
four-day official visit to the island country starting from
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Greece's four F-16 fighters and two C-130 transport
planes landed at the air base near the town of Paphos in western
Cyprus, triggering strong protests from Turkey and Turkish
Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
Turkey retaliated by sending six F-16 fighters to northern
Cyprus to show its determination to protect Turkish Cypriots
living in the northern part of the island.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been at odds over a number of issues
concerning the Mediterranean and Aegean, the settlement of the
knotty Cyprus problem in particular.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which keeps close relations with Greece and
Turkey, has been trying to mediate between the two foes, but no
substantial improvement in bilateral ties has been made so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
