<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Measures Introduced to Curb Price Fall of Meat and Sugar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government is taking
fresh measures to curb the downturn of the prices of meat and
sugar in a bid to protect the enthusiasm of the producers.
</P>
<P>
Due to a continuous rise in output, the purchasing price of
live pigs fell from 7.91 yuan (0.95 US dollars) to 5.8 yuan per
kilogram from January to May, and this was the lowest ever
recorded since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the record-high output of sugar also brought down
the price of sugar to the lowest since 1993.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, many of the pig-raisers in pig-producing areas
have begun killing mother pigs. If the trend is going on uncurbed,
the farmers' enthusiasm will be seriously hurt," a market analyst
said.
</P>
<P>
In order to address the problem, the State Bureau of Internal
Trade which supervises commodity marketing and storing, has worked
out five major measures:
</P>
<P>
Since April, the Bureau has coordinated the selling of
slaughtered pigs from producing to consuming regions and in
storing more pork in state-run warehouses.
</P>
<P>
An amount of imported sugar has been shifted as state reserves
instead of putting it onto the market.
</P>
<P>
An urgent circular was issued calling for local governments to
ensure more purchasing funds and subsidies and increase the
storage of meat and sugar.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have been made to step up the purchase of meat and
sugar by state-owned purchasing companies and to organize more
exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
