<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Use Cuttlefish Ink to Treat Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, June 27 (Xinhua) -- While Chinese scientists in Shanghai
are trying to use the toxic white arsenic to treat cancer, some
other scientists in east China's Shandong Province claimed that
they are managing to turn cancer cells into normal ones with
non-toxic cuttlefish ink.
</P>
<P>
Headed by Sun Keren, professor at the toxicology research
institute of Shandong Medical Science University, scientists
probed a new way to treat cancer patients by using a kind of
non-toxic biological pharmaceutical with a special material
extracted from cuttlefish ink and rare traditional Chinese
medicinal herbs.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the cancer cells are developed from variant normal
cells. Chemical and radiation therapies are usually applied after
the patients undergo operations.
</P>
<P>
However, those methods kill a large amount of healthy cells
while killing cancer cells. So scientists worldwide are seeking a
non-toxic method to treat the deadly cancers.
</P>
<P>
After eight years research, Sun and his colleagues have used
their self-developed pharmaceutical to cause abnormal development
of thew cancer information transmission system which impels cancer
cells to turn to become normal ones.
</P>
<P>
Doctors said the pharmaceutical can also curb the deceasing of
white blood cells and enhance patients' immunological function.
</P>
<P>
Clinic use of the pharmaceutical indicated that the rate for
curbing the development of cancers reaches 70.8 percent and 98
percent of patients under radiation or chemical treatment
therapies have their white blood cells increased after taking the
pharmaceutical.
</P>
<P>
Sun's research will focus on the industrialization of the
cuttlefish-ink pharmaceutical.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
