<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remains of Famous Porcelain Kiln Complex Found in Henan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Remains of four porcelain kilns
dating back to the Northern Song Dynasty (960-1127) have been
found in Baofeng county in central China's Henan province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists regard it as a proof that the site was
where Ruyao Kiln, one of the most famous kiln complex in the
dynasty, was located. The kiln was noted for its celadon ware made
for imperial family.
</P>
<P>
In 1987, the archaeologists unearthed there remains of a
workshop and tens of porcelain pieces and gather that Baofeng was
probably the site of Ruyao Kiln. Yet no remains of kilns have been
discovered previously.
</P>
<P>
The newly-found kilns are in the shape of a horse's hoof. One
of them is so well preserved that it can be restored easily and
will contribute to the study of celadon-making in the Northern
Song Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
Porcelain pieces found at the site suggest that the site was
operational during the period from the Northern Song to the Yuan
Dynasty (1271-1368). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
