<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residence of Ceylon Prince's Offspring Found in Quanzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The residence of an offspring of a
Ceylon prince who came to China some 500 years ago has been found
in Quanzhou city in east China's Fujian province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese historians value the residence as it provides an
evidence for the relationship between China and ancient Ceylon, or
today's Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
According to the experts, the residence, as well as the
mausoleum of the prince's offsprings, are evidence of Sino-Ceylon
relationship ever found in China.
</P>
<P>
Historical records have shown that a crown prince of Ceylon was
sent to China in 1459, when the country was under the rule of the
Ming Dynasty (1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
Seven years later, his father, then the king of Ceylon, died
and his cousin took over the crown. The prince could no longer go
back to his motherland and settled in Quanzhou, then a famouse
seaport of China.
</P>
<P>
The newly-found residence was first built some 300 years ago in
the Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) by Shi Quanguan, an offspring of the
Ceylon prince who changed his family name into "Shi".
</P>
<P>
According to the title deed owned presently by Lin Jinzheng,
the house was sold to a family with the surname of Yuan in 1783
and in 1885 it was sold again to a family with the surname of Lin.
</P>
<P>
The brick house in the Quanzhou local style, covering an area
of some 800 sq m, was kept intact with original flower pots and
fish bowls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
