<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's VP to Hold Talks With Squatters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Zibabwean African
National Union (Patriotic Front) (ZANU-PF) has tasked Zimbabwean
Vice-President Simon Muzenda to persuade the Svosve villagers to
vacate the farms they have forcibly occupied.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for administration of the party Didymus Mutasa told
the Zimbabwe News Agency in an interview Friday that the central
committee of the party's 34th ordinary session held in Harare
Friday had tasked Muzenda to persuade villagers from Svosve
communal area to recognize the need to be orderly resettled.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of the Svosve people was mentioned in passing
during the meeting and Vice-President Muzenda was assigned to go
there tomorrow to try and talk to them so that they realize what
is happening and the fact that there are farms earmarked for
orderly resettlement in Mashonaland East Province," he said.
</P>
<P>
The land-hungry villagers in Svosve communal lands, about 80
kilometers east of Harare, last week marched onto commercial
farms in the area and vowed to stay put, accusing the government
of not acting speedily on its planned resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
They have already begun putting up shelters.
</P>
<P>
President Mugabe has ruled out the use of force to evict them,
saying they had genuine reasons to demand resettlement but should
wait to be orderly resettled.
</P>
<P>
The analysts in Harare said the Svosve issue had far-reaching
ramifications, including dampening investor confidence. They
also expressed fear that if the government was not tough enough
on the villagers, other villagers elsewhere would also illegally
resettle themselves.
</P>
<P>
President Mugabe Friday urged his ruling ZANU-PF government to
move fast on land redistribution program to avoid anarchy.
</P>
