<HEADLINE> Door to Negotiation with Dalai Lama Is Open: Jiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua)-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin told
a press conference here today that the door to negotiation with
the Dalai Lama is open so long as the Dalai Lama recognizes that
Tibet is an inalienable part of China and that Taiwan is a
province of China.
</P>
<P>
"Actually we have several channels of communication with him. I
hope (to see) positive changes in the Dalai Lama," Jiang added.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks in response to an earlier statement by
U.S. President Clinton that he had urged Jiang to resume a
dialogue with the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
"President Clinton is also interested in the question of the
Dalai Lama. Actually since the Dalai Lama left (Tibet) in 1959,
earth-shaking changes have taken place in Tibet and theocracy has
gone forever, although the disappearance of this system in Tibet
is much later than that in Europe after Renaissance," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"More than one million serfs under the rule of the Dalai Lama
were liberated and I visited a liberated serf's family in 1990,"
Jiang noted, adding that the system of national autonomy is in
practice in Tibet and people there have their Tibet Autonomous
Region government.
</P>
<P>
"Since I came to work in the central government, I have urged
the rest 29 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions to
assist Tibet in its development, even including those provinces
that are not developed such as Qinghai," Jiang said, stressing the
fact that 8 billion Yuan (RMB) has been spent on Tibet and 62
projects have been accomplished there," Jiang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
