<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Send Five or Six Sports to Asiad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Only athletes from five or six
sports deserve to go to the 13th Asian Games in Bangkok in
December, a minister was quoted by local press Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The deserving athletes were from badminton, karate,
weightlifting, tennis and boxing, Minister of sports and Youth
Affairs Agung Laksono said, adding that other sports only held
slim chances of bagging medals in the quadrennial sporting event.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, The National Sports Council announced that the
country's athletes would compete in 21 sports in the hope of
winning six or seven gold medals.
</P>
<P>
On a visit to the national badminton training center in East
Jakarta on Friday, Agung said that the lack of international
achievements coupled with lack of funds should prod several sports
organizations to reconsider their efforts to send their athletes.
</P>
<P>
"The contingent is not necessarily big in quantity, but the
important things are quality and chances to win medals," he added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia only excelled in badminton at the previous Asian
Games in Hiroshima, Japan, four years ago, winning all of its
three gold medals in the event. In the upcoming Asian Games,
Indonesia will likely rely on badminton players in its medal hunt.
</P>
<P>
The badminton association's deputy in charge of athlete
development Mangombar Ferdinand Siregar told Agung that the
association had drawn up a master training plan for the Sydney
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The association would shortlist between 42 and 48 shuttlers
from the 63 players currently at the training center, Siregar
said.
</P>
<P>
"If everything goes as expected, we will give the
Olympics-bound players the privilege to take part in international
tournaments," he added.
</P>
<P>
The race for Olympic qualifying will start in April next year
and finish 12 months later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
