<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jamuna Bridge to Bring High Rate of Economic Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The 4.8-kilometer-long Bangabandhu
Jamuma Bridge, the longest bridge in Bangladesh as well as in
south Asia which opened to traffic Tuesday, may have an annual
economic rate of return at 22 percent, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The feasibility studies of the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank (ADB) showed a healthy rate of return, A.H.M.
Abdullah, deputy project manager of the bridge, was quoted by
press reports Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
"A healthy rate of return is expected to come from the bridge
and it may go up from the previous estimate of 14.9 percent,"
considering the traffic volume in the last few days after the
opening of the bridge, an ADB expert said.
</P>
<P>
The bridge would not only pay off all its foreign debts of 600
million U.S. dollars by the year 2033, but also earn an impressive
net income, in view of the anticipated daily traffic demand and
its earnings as a facility provider for railway, power, and
telecommunications, according to Abdullah.
</P>
<P>
The power transmission lines with the bridge, for example,
would reduce the cost of supplying power to the west of the
country which would otherwise request a power interconnector
across the Jamuan River at a much higher cost, he said. This
helped to increase the economic rate of return substantially, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Toll collection from vehicles across the bridge was estimated
at 50-60 million taka (about 1.09-1.3 million dollars) per month.
"Collection of the first two days indicates the monthly toll
collection will be 50-60 million taka (about 1.09-1.30 million
dollars)," resulting in an annual collection from the bridge
ranging between 600-720 million taka (about 13.04-15.65 million
dollars), an official of the bridge authority said.
</P>
<P>
Initially authorities have fixed the target of annual toll from
the country's largest development project at 530 million taka
(about 11.52 million dollars) that may rise up to 7 billion taka
(about 152.17 million dollars) by the year 2033, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, about 35,000 to 40,000 jobs might be generated
each year in the country's northern region after the opening of
the bridge, according to an ADB survey conducted in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the 950 million-dollar multipurpose bridge,
which was funded by the Bangladeshi government, the World Bank,
the ADB and Japan, started in October 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
