<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- NBA Washington Wizards player
Juwan Howard denied that he made a sexual assault to a woman, and
is seeking 20 million U.S. dollars from the accuser for his
reputation and image damage.
</P>
<P>
Howard's lawyer filed the civil suit Friday in Montgomery
County Circuit Court in Maryland. The suit seeks compensation for
emotional distress caused by the charges made by a Connecticut
woman.
</P>
<P>
The woman dialed 911 and told police that she was sexually
assaulted during a party on April 6 at Howard's home. She also
mentioned Howard's teammate Chris Webber's name.
</P>
<P>
"This woman's allegations have done irreparable harm to my
reputation and image," Howard said in a statement by his lawyer
Mitchell Rubinstein on TV. "It was important to me to take legal
action in order to restore my good reputation and deter anyone
from making such false claims against me in the future."
</P>
<P>
The woman's lawyer Ned Collier said his client would respond to
Howard's suit with one of her own, this time in civil court.
</P>
<P>
"My client told the truth in front of the grand jury, she told
the truth to me and she will tell the truth in court again," the
lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
Webber and Howard denied any wrongdoing in the sexual assault
case. 
</P>
