<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Is Right on Resolving Tiananmen Disturbances: Jiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Had the Chinese Government not
taken resolute measures to deal with the political disturbances in
1989, China would not enjoy the stability that it is enjoying
today, President Jiang Zemin said here today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks at a joint press conference with U.S.
President Bill Clinton in the Great Hall of the People at noon
today.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question from Xinhua about China's position
concerning the human rights issue and apparently showing
disagreement to an earlier allusion by President Clinton to the
Tiananmen Square incident in June 1989, Jiang said that the
Chinese people "have long drawn a historical conclusion" on this
incident.
</P>
<P>
He noted that today the Chinese Government solemnly commits
itself to the promotion and protection of human rights and
fundamental freedoms.
</P>
<P>
"China stresses that top priority should be given to the rights
to subsistence and the rights to development," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the meanwhile, he noted, "efforts should be made to
strengthen democracy and legal system building and to protect the
economic, social, cultural, civil and political rights of the
people."
</P>
<P>
Jiang went on to say that the Chinese nation always respects
and maintains the dignity and the rights of people.
</P>
<P>
He quoted an ancient Chinese thinker more than 2,000 years ago
as saying that "among all the living things nurtured between
heaven and earth, the most valuable is human beings."
</P>
<P>
"China and the United States have differences and also have
common grounds on the human rights issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the two countries differ in social system, ideology,
historical, cultural and traditional backgrounds, he said, they
have different ways and means to realize human rights and
fundamental freedoms.
</P>
<P>
"So it's nothing strange that we may have some difference of
views over some issues," President Jiang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
