<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Denies Concession Made in Detargeting Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has
denied that the U.S. side has made any concession in the course
of reaching an agreement with China on not to target their
respective nuclear missiles at each other's countries.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question from a U.S. journalist whether concessions
have been made on the joint press conference hosted by the two
presidents, Clinton said "the short answer...and the accurate one
is No."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the U.S. position on the issue has been products
of decades of experience that has not been changed.
</P>
<P>
Clinton elaborated that the agreement is a mutual decision to
eliminate the chance of any accidental launch of each's nuclear
missiles and to take one more step in showing mutual confidence
and trust in one anther.
</P>
<P>
The decision is also a "helpful signal as a counterweight to
the recent nuclear tests in India and Pakistan," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chinese President Jiang Zemin pointed out the
agreement shows to the whole world that China and the U.S. are
partners rather than adversaries, and reiterated that China will
not be the first to use nuclear weapons under any circumstances, a
promise China has kept since the very day it came into possession
of nuclear weapons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
