<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Parliament Passes 1999 Budget Despite Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's House of
Representatives approved the 825 billion baht (20.1 billion U.S.
dollar) budget for fiscal 1999 late Friday night after the
opposition staged a walkout.
</P>
<P>
As The Nation reported Saturday, the opposition said the budget
was unacceptable because it was not in line with the economic
situation and had only been prepared to improve the government's
stability.
</P>
<P>
However, House members voted 205 to nil in favor of the Budget
Bill at the first reading after a three-day debate and set up a
special committee to scrutinize it.
</P>
<P>
Before the debate ended after mid-night, the opposition New
Aspiration Party legislators walked out in protest.
</P>
<P>
The budget will carry a 25 billion baht (609.8 million dollars)
deficit, and revenue collections would not come as "overly
estimated" under the economic crunch, the opposition said.
</P>
<P>
With such a budget, the government would not succeed in curing
the economic woes, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
