<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployment Rate Declines in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The percentage of the unemployed
in Sri Lanka's labor force declined from 13.1 percent in 1994 to
10.3 percent last year, according to the Department of Census and
Statistics (DCS) here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The number of Sri Lanka's unemployed people declined from
797,591 in 1994 to 644,870 in 1997. However, in the previous three
years from 1991 to 1994 the decline in the number of the
unemployed was only 64,089, the DCS sources said.
</P>
<P>
The unemployed comprised 319,383 (49,5 percent) males and
325,487 (50.5 percent) females in 1997. More than 80 percent of
the unemployed are youths in the age groups of 18 to 29.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate is highest among persons who have the
General Certificate of Education (Ordinary Level), the sources
stated.
</P>
<P>
A large number of employed persons, about 38 percent, are
engaged in the agricultural sector while 15.6 percent are engaged
in the manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
The main reason for the decline in unemployment is due to the
setting up of many new industries during the past three years,
said the sources, adding that in the next three years Sri Lanka
proposes to push projects to develop the rural areas and provide
more employment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
