<HEADLINE> China, U.S. to Strengthen Dialogues, Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese and U.S. heads of
state have agreed to strengthen dialogues and cooperation
between the two countries on major international issues.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin made the announcement at the
joint press conference shortly after his formal talks with his
U.S. counterpart in the Great Hall of the People earlier today.
</P>
<P>
Under the new historical circumstances, Jiang said: "common
interests of China and the United States is not reducing, but
increasing; and the foundation for bilateral cooperation is not
weakened, but consolidated."
</P>
<P>
Jiang added the two presidents hold that China and the U.S., as
permanent members of the United Nations Security Council, should
continue to make concerted efforts to promote peace and stability
in the Asia Pacific region and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should also work together to alleviate and
eradicate various tensions, prevent the proliferation of massive
destructive weapons, Jiang and Clinton agreed, according to Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said they hold that their common efforts should be also
directed to environmental protection, cracking down on
international crime, drug trafficking and international terrorism,
and promoting the economic growth of the world.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-U.S. relations are improving and developing, Jiang
stressed, and the two sides have made significant progress in
cooperation in many areas.  
</P>
