<HEADLINE> Latin American Cultural News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are news items
on culture, arts, and entertainment in Latin America over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Leandro, the famous Brazilian balladist, died
of lung cancer at the age of 36 on Tuesday at the Sao Luiz de Sao
Paulo hospital after eight days in a coma.
</P>
<P>
One of two brothers in the duet "Leandro and Leonardo," the
artist, whose real name was Luiz Jose Costa, became famous in
South America 20 years ago for his rural theme songs.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- "The biggest single batch of seafood soup ready
for human consumption immediately ... in the World" will be
prepared by a group of residents of Ciudad del Carmen, Campeche,
in southeast Mexico in mid July.
</P>
<P>
Miguel Angel Illescas, a member of the municipal committee of
the National Action Party (PAN), said enough soup would be
prepared to feed 8,000 people. About 30 cooks will work to make
the soup, which will be served at the "La Concordia" baseball
stadium.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The seventh edition of the Iberoamerican Art Fair
(FIA-98) will be on July 1-6 in Venezuela. It will offer a varied
and updated sample of national and international art.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- The 32nd International Iberoamerican Literature
Congress will be on June 29 to July 2 in Santiago, the first such
gathering held in Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
