<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Develop Corn Cultivation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 27 (Xinhua) -- World Health Organization (WHO)
has granted 50 million U.S. dollars in a bid to popularize and
develop the cultivation of corn in Sri Lanka, according to
Agriculture Ministry sources here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the corn could be cultivated as Sri Lanka's
climate was suitable, but the country has been cultivating a
little of corn in the past.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the WHO's grant, the ministry had taken several steps
to popularize corn cultivation and a four-year plan has been
drawn up.
</P>
<P>
The plan is being implemented from June this year, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the ministry aims to harvest 32,000 tons of
corn before the end of this year and 151,000 tons in the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
A total of 15,000 hectares of land have been utilized for corn
cultivation in Anuradhapura district in the Central Northern
Province for the 97-98 season, said the sources, adding that a
special program has already been launched by the state and private
sector traders to buy the corn harvest of 20,000 tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
