<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A police source Saturday confirmed
a newspaper report that U.S. FBI agents stormed a Bangkok
apartment Friday and arrested four foreign nationals suspected of
involvement in the 1993 World Trade Center bombing in New York.
</P>
<P>
The suspects belong to a Moslem extremist group that
masterminded the blast, the source said on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's Nation Newspaper quoted U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation officers as saying the four men were suspected of
planning to assassinate the U.S. ambassador to Thailand and launch
a terrorist attack on the U.S. Embassy compound.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the suspects -- Mohamad Rahim, 30, Hadja Pahu
Sasa, 25, Hara Haj Husem, 26, and Hareef Hussen, 25 -- had made
contact with several Thai suppliers to obtain weapons for their
operations. The paper said the suspects are Pakistani nationals.
</P>
<P>
Thai immigration police, acting on an FBI tip-off, traced the
suspects to their hideaway and made the arrests, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It said U.S. Ambassador to Thailand William Itoh and a group of
U.S. officials later visited the Suan Pllu headquarters of the
Immigration Police where the four suspects were being held.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. Embassy spokesman acknowledged that an investigation of
the suspects' activities in Thailand was under way. But he said
that at present he could not link the suspects with the World
Trade Center bombing, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The bombing killed six people and wounded more than 1,000
others. Damage was estimated at more than 500 million U.S.
dollars. Six men were convicted in the United States between 1994
and 1997 in connection with the attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
