<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia, Russia Stress Political Dialogue on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia and Russia said Friday
that all disputed issues on Kosovo should be settled through
political dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The consensus was reached after Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic met with Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Nikolai
Afanasyevsky, who was completing a working visit here. The
minister's visit began last Sunday, Yugoslav news agency Tanjug
reported.
</P>
<P>
Both agree that Yugoslavia's territorial integrity and
sovereignty are inviolable and the attacks and provocation by
Albanian terrorists there should be criticized.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 people have been killed since the outbreak of
armed conflict between ethnic Albanians and Serb police in
Kosovo. The troubled province is now under the threat of
escalating and expanding conflicts.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Milosevic and Afanasyevsky reiterated their
determination to further enhance bilateral relations, reports
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
