<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank Moves to Ease Interest Burden </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 27 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand, the
country's central bank, took a new step Friday to ease its grip on
monetary policy by lowering interest rates on the bond repurchase
market below 17 percent, the Bangkok Post reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The move was positively received by the market as a step toward
easing the pressing interest burden on the corporate sector, the
newspaper quoted central bank governor Chatumongol Sonakul as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange rates were also trading in a satisfactory
range without any intervention by the central bank, the governor
said when commenting on the new move.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the baht traded late at 41.45/55 to the U.S. dollar,
compared with 41.16/26 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The overnight interest rate through the bond repurchase market
was 16.875 percent, down from 17.25 percent on Thursday. Interbank
rates on Friday ranged from 17-18 percent.
</P>
<P>
Apart from complaints from the country's corporate sector, many
foreign analysts had also called for the central bank to lower
interest rates to ease the credit crunch.
</P>
<P>
Chatumongol said he believed the economic contraction of
Thailand would not reach 7-8 percent this year, since the country
has a strong agricultural base and relative social stability.
</P>
<P>
Pressure on the capital account has also eased as the rollover
rate of foreign loans remains high, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
