<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy Promises Efforts to Resolve Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. envoy
to the Balkans, said here Friday the United States will do
everything possible to help secure a peaceful settlement regarding
the Kosovo crisis, the Tanjug News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke warned at a press conference after meeting Kosovo
Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova that the situation in Kosovo is
"very dangerous."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that all efforts should be made to prevent the
fighting in Kosovo from escalating into a war.
</P>
<P>
NATO is very concerned over the Kosovo issue, the envoy
said. NATO is now working on actions to take if the Kosovo
conflicts turns into war and spreads beyond the Yugoslav border.
</P>
<P>
Decisions will be made only by President Bill Clinton when
mobilization of NATO forces involves the United States, Holbrooke
noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the next few days will be dedicated to strengthening
diplomatic mediations between Belgrade and Pristina, the
provincial capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The envoy said on Thursday the international community was
opposed to the independence of Kosovo and conceded that Kosovo is
part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo has sunk into chaos since pro-independence ethnic
Albanians clashed with local Serb police in February. More than
300 people have been killed since then.
</P>
<P>
Conflicts in the troubled province are now threatening to
escalate and spill over into neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
