<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Enterprise Mergers Promote China's Industrial Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 27 (Xinhua) -- South-north enterprise mergers
are going strong in China, aimed at reshaping the country's
state-owned industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
The electronics industry of northeast China's Liaoning
province, the country's major heavy industrial base, for example,
has witnessed a surge of mergers and purchasing, involving
enterprises in south China.
</P>
<P>
The province has some high-tech enterprises that have been
doing well in manufacturing color TVs, refrigerators and washing
machines since the early 1980s. But most of them are facing a
declining market due to poor management and operation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, producers of electrical appliances in south China
have made excellent achievements, and they are seeking for
opportunities to expand their market shares and gain more benefits.
</P>
<P>
Kelon Group, China's largest refrigerator producer in Shunde
city of Guangdong province, for example, took the lead in entering
north China, financing the formation of the Yingkou-Kelon
Corporation with the Yingkou Refrigerator Plant, Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
"Kelon will set up a huge production and marketing system by
the end of the century, based in Shunde while developing two wings
in Yingkou of northeast China and Chengdu of Sichuan province,
southwest China, in an effort to manufacture three million
refrigerators annually", said Jin Changwei, deputy general manager
of the Yingkou-Kelon Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Other high-tech giants from Guangdong, Shandong, Shanxi and
Shanghai are also doing the same. "It's of strategic significance
to group small businesses into large enterprises to face
competition in the domestic and world market", said Wang Jiaqi,
deputy manager of a joint venture between Fushun city of Liaoning
and the Hi-Sense Electrical Appliances Group of Qingdao,
Shandong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
