<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rice Production to Drop by 6.25 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's unhusked rice output
is expected to drop by 6.25 percent to 46.29 million tons this
year due to the planting season being delayed by the drought,
according to the Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said Friday the severe drought which hit the country
last year and delayed the rice planting season, affected the
supply of water to many rice-producing regions and led to reduced
yields and crop failure.
</P>
<P>
The drought reduced rice planting areas by 4.13 percent to
10.68 million hectares this year from 11.14 million hectares last
year, the bureau said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Reduction of fertilizers and pesticides used in rice farming
has also resulted in a downward trend in the volume of rice
production, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
However, the bureau announced increased production of several
other crops. For instance, the country's corn production this year
is expected to reach 9.17 million tons, up 4.56 percent from 8.77
million tons last year.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is expected to import 3.1 million tons of rice from
Thailand, India, China, Vietnam and Pakistan to make up for the
shortage in domestic production this year, official sources said
earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
