<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retired U.S. Commander Denies Use of Nerve Gas to Kill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A retired Army commander of a
U.S. military operation on Friday denied the alleged use of nerve
gas to kill defectors during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
"Tailwind was a diversionary mission. It was not to kill
defectors or POWs or anything like that," Army Col. Eugene
McCarley who was a captain at the time he led the mission, told
500 members of the Special Forces Association at its annual
meeting in Albuquerque, New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the CNN and Time magazine reported that
their research over eight months indicated that sarin nerve gas
was used by U.S. forces in about 20 operations in northern Vietnam
and in the so-called secret war in Laos.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Tailwind mission was aimed at killing U.S.
defectors and up to 20 American military defectors may have been
killed.
</P>
<P>
"The CNN report was absolutely wrong," McCarley said, "I think
we fought a good fight."
</P>
<P>
A key source of the CNN-Time report was retired Admiral Thomas
Moorer, a Vietnam-era chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. He
has since backed away from his account.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William Cohen has ordered an official
investigation into the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
