<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern Life Built for Ethnic Folks of Rocky Mountains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Cutting through the desolate rocky
mountain, one arrives at the Disu Township where the scene changes
quite dramatically. In sight are two- and three-story villas
inlaid with colorful ceramic tiles. Mitsubishi and Toyota
cross-country jeeps are running against the hot breeze of June.
</P>
<P>
In the homes of local folks, one can see an abundance of modern
home appliances such as color televisions, telephones and
electrical water heaters, as well as stockpiles of rattan-woven
handicraft articles.
</P>
<P>
It is these rattan articles plus a thriving market economy that
have turned a dream for modern life into reality for the folks of
one of the poorest mountain areas in China.
</P>
<P>
Disu Township is located on a rocky mountain in the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region in south China. Nothing grows on the
mountain except rattans and grass. The severe shortage of arable
land made the township's 48,100 people live under poverty even in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
By chance, Wei Changying, a young fellow of the yao ethnic
group, learned in 1994 that rattan-woven wares, which local folks
made for exchanging salt and matches, could be sold to foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
Wearing clothes of home-woven cotton cloth and carrying rattan
ware samples, the shy-looking Wei turned up during the annual
export commodity fair held in Guangzhou in the spring of that year.
</P>
<P>
The exquisite flower baskets and Christmas gifts caught the
immediate attention of businessmen, and deals worth 15,000 yuan
(1,807 US dollars) were clinched.
</P>
<P>
Ever since, the dozen varieties of rattan growing out of the
rocky mountain have become a huge source of wealth. Orders from
the United States, Britain, Japan, France, and Holland have flaked
in.
</P>
<P>
Now over 90 percent of the township's labor force are involved
in the business. In 1997, the township turned out 23 million yuan
(2.71 million US dollars) worth of rattan articles which were sold
to over 20 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
The successful business has brought incredible wealth to the
once poor township. Take Danyang Village for example. Now 95
percent of the households have built multi-story houses. The
families have bought 30 imported jeeps each worth over 300,000
yuan plus a dozen less-expensive cars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Welcomes U.S. President (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
presided over a red-carpet welcoming ceremony in honor of U.S.
President William Clinton on a state visit to China in the plaza
east of the Great Hall of the People this morning.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and his wife Hillary arrived at the plaza at 9:00
(local time) and warmly shook hands with Chinese President Jiang
Zemin and his wife Wang Yeping who were waiting for them there.
</P>
<P>
Two Chinese teenagers presented the Clintons with bouquets of
fresh flowers.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is the fifth incumbent U.S. president to visit China
after Richard Nixon, Gerald Ford, Ronald Reagan and George Bush.
</P>
<P>
After introducing their own respective government officials
present to each other, the heads of state of the two nations
walked onto the reviewing stand. A 60-member military band of
the People's Liberation Army (PLA) played the anthems of the
United States and China while 21-gun salute was fired.
</P>
<P>
Then the leader of the guard of honor of the three PLA services
marched to the front of the reviewing stand and reported to
President Clinton: "Mr. President, the guard of honor of the three
PLA services is ready, please review."
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by Jiang, Clinton descended from the stand and
reviewed the guard of honor composed 176 PLA soldiers and
officers.
</P>
<P>
After the welcoming ceremony which ended at 9:14, the heads of
state of the two nations walked into the Great Hall of the People
to begin official talks.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 people from various walks of life of both China and
the United States attended the welcoming ceremony.
</P>
</TEXT>
