<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tumor Necrosin Believed Effective in AIDS Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, June 27 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese Danish professor claimed
that the necrosin of tumor inside the human body may be effective
in the treatment and prevention of the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
Tan Jinquan, visiting professor at the Anhui Medical Science
University, said he will engage in the research in the next three
years to find if his inference is true.
</P>
<P>
The government of east China's Anhui Province and the
university have decided to spend 1 million yuan (120,000
U.S. dollars) on the research program.
</P>
<P>
The 46-year-old professor said scientists found in 1975 that
lab mice would have cell tissue that has immunity and could cause
necrosis of tumor after injection of BCG vaccine. Scientists
called the tissue "necrosin of tumor."
</P>
<P>
After 10 years research, Tan found that the necrosin of tumor
could keep the AIDS virus under control.
</P>
<P>
He said when the AIDS virus infects the human body, its needs a
"tunnel" inside the human body, while the necrosin of tumor could
block the moving of AIDS virus cells.
</P>
<P>
His inference has been proved by lab experiments on mice.
</P>
<P>
The professor has already published his latest discovery on
British magazine "Immunology" and the article was later cited by
U.S. "Science" magazine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
