<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Figure in Italian Mafia Arrested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Italian police scaled a five-story
building in Bovalino, a city in southern Italy, on Friday to
arrest a mobster who is said to be a leading figure in the
"Ndrangheta," the Calabrian mafia.
</P>
<P>
According to police, Antonio Romeo, 42, one of the 500 most
dangerous criminals sought by police, is the head of a "cupola" or
governing body of the Ndrangheta and had close relations with
organized crime in South America, eastern Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
Police entered his top floor apartment while he slept. The
doors and windows of the apartment were armored to prevent attacks
or unauthorized entry.
</P>
<P>
The police assault was spearheaded by agents with
mountaineering skills, as a police offical put it, they possessed
"acrobatic gifts."
</P>
<P>
Romeo, nicknamed "the lawyer" because he was a law graduate,
had been sought by police since March, 1993. He had been
sentenced to over 50 years in prison for mafia association and
international trafficking in heroin and cocaine.
</P>
<P>
According to investigators, Romeo took over as the
"Ndrangheta's boss of bosses" from his father, Sebastiano Romeo,
who died under house arrest in January at the age of 67. 
</P>
</TEXT>
