<HEADLINE> Prodi Comments on Historic Visit to Iran Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
is scheduled to arrive in Tehran on June 30 for a two-day visit to
Iran, the first by a Western head of government since 1978.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's visit comes as a result of the European Union's
decision in February to restore top-level contacts with Iran, and
of Italy's own strategic interest in the Mediterranean area,
according to a statement from the prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
Italy wants to learn whether Iran's increasing openness to the
West and the reformist stance of President Mohammed Khatami has
actually born fruit inside the country, a spokesman for the prime
minister said.
</P>
<P>
"It's an exclusively political visit to understand (the
situation in Iran)," said Ricardo Franco Levi.
</P>
<P>
Italy has consistently backed a line of dialogue with Iran,
seeing it as essential not to alienate a key player in the Middle
East balance of power.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Levi stressed that Italy has never broken ranks
with its Western allies in policy towards Iran and is not doing so
now.
</P>
<P>
"All our allies know about this visit," he said. "They know
that they will be informed of whatever emerges from it and the
Iranians know this too."
</P>
<P>
The groundwork for the visit, during which Prodi will meet
President Khatami and other top Iranian politicians, was laid by
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini, who went to Tehran in early March.
</P>
<P>
Dini said Thursday that Italy wanted the West to support
President Khatami and encourage the openness he proposes.
</P>
<P>
Khatami won a landslide election victory last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
