<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Island Province Free From Red Tides (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, June 27 (Xinhua) -- Old Zeng, a fish breeder in
Qionghai of south China's Hainan province, expects a good harvest
and handsome returns this year as he is sure of the good quality
of the environment that guarantees his business success.
</P>
<P>
He didn't, however, feel so good only one or two months ago,
when he learned that red tides were frequently occurring in the
waters off Hong Kong and Guangdong that are not far away.
</P>
<P>
"I felt worried every day then, afraid that misfortune might
fall, but now it seems unnecessary for me to worry about it
anymore as specialists have assured me red tides will not come,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Specialists say that the red tide is mainly caused by
pollutants from land and excessive marine cultivation. But Hainan
province has never been invaded by large-scale destructive red
tides since 1988, and the province's sea areas will be free from
red tides for a long time to come thanks to the sound
environmental quality and the steps taken by the local government
to protect the marine environment.
</P>
<P>
"Although red tides occurred in part of the province's sea
waters some time ago, pollution was brought under control soon and
the general situation of the province's marine environment has
been kept as good as it is," said Chen Cheng, director of the
provincial oceanic department.
</P>
<P>
The water quality of more than 80 percent of Hainan's sea area
has been among the best in the country, according to a recent survey
conducted by the National People's Congress's oceanic environment
law enforcement inspection team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Island Province Free From Red Tide (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The provincial government has put environmental protection on
its top agenda from the very beginning. A 1,500-km coastal forest
belt has fixed shifting sand and prevented land erosion on the
island.
</P>
<P>
"To prevent the possible deterioration of the oceanic
environment, we must bring land pollution under strict control,"
said Li Fude, director of the law and regulation office of the
provincial oceanic department.
</P>
<P>
The province has closed down 75 polluting enterprises in past
two years, setting deadlines for another 400 enterprises to meet
pullutant discharge standards, and refused to grant approval for
any polluting project to be launched.
</P>
<P>
Most of the province's industrial projects are located in the
western part and a license system for discharging pollutants has
been established to control the total volume of urban pollutant
discharge.
</P>
<P>
An urban waste water treatment plant and 12 industrial waste
water treatment plants have been set up in the provincial capital
of Haikou, which has a population of over 600,000. With loans from
the German government, the city is also building another waste
water treatment plant with a daily capacity of 300,000 tons, which
will be put into operation by the end of the year to handle more
than 95 percent of the city's waste water.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the construction of a garbage treatment plant with
loans from Norway is also in full swing. After completion of these
treatment facilities, all the city's wastes can be handled
properly, experts said.
</P>
<P>
The ecological resources of mangrove and coral reef have been
effectively protected, with 13 natural protection zones
established along the island's 1,500-km sea shores, which have
become a shelter belt against oceanic pollution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Island Province Free From Red Tide (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tourism resources have been developed in Sanya in the island's
southern tip whose coral protection zone is famous for its
beautiful landscape, and a waste water treatment plant with daily
capacity of 80,000 tons is also being constructed in the city.
</P>
<P>
Environmental protection awareness has been enhanced among the
island's residents, who have spontaneously worked out many local
rules on protecting their environment.
</P>
<P>
The mangrove in Dongzhai port in Qiongshan city has spread to
cover an area of 2,000 hectares, which has been listed by the
International Wetland Organization.
</P>
<P>
In sea water fish breeding zones in Sanya, Qionghai and
Lingshui, fish breeders cultivate fish under the guidance of
technicians to avoid causing pollution to the sea waters.
</P>
<P>
The island province strengthens oceanic pollution treatment and
control while stepping up marine transportation and oil
exploration. All ships of more than 100 tonnages have been
equipped with facilities to retrieve waste oil, and have their
pollution discharge recorded to meet inspection.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 law-enforcement organs have been established in 13
coastal cities and counties to conduct supervision and
administration over sea areas, and inspection teams are frequently
sent to oil-exploration platforms to oversee pollutant discharge.
</P>
<P>
The province has handled 130 cases involving marine
environmental pollution in the past ten years.
</P>
<P>
The sound marine ecological environment has provided a larger
space for the province's development in the next century. The
provincial government has listed the marine industry as its
economic pillar. The province's total output of marine economy is
expected to reach 15 billion yuan (about 1.9 billion US dollars)
by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
