<HEADLINE> Nicaragua Starts Cattle Exports to Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Nicaragua is ready to export some
1,800 heads of cattle to Mexico under a new free trade arrangement
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
This is Nicaragua's first export of cattle on the hoof since
1977, Agriculture Minister Mario de Franco said after signing an
amendment on Friday to two support projects in the cattle raising
sector.
</P>
<P>
Mexican importers are offering a price of 9.6 cordobas (less
than one U.S. dollar) per kilogram for the cattle, higher than
what is paid by local slaughterhouses.
</P>
<P>
De Franco predicted that the international prices of beef would
go up next year to level the historical record in 1975.
</P>
<P>
The free trade agreement between Nicaragua and Mexico provides
for a comfortable quota of access with zero tariff for Nicaragua's
exports to the Mexican market, in respect to beef, powered milk
and non-processed cheese. 
</P>
