<HEADLINE> Spokesman Denies Alleged Arrests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 27 (Xinhua) -- China has not arrested or detained
any of the persons whom the Western media reported during U.S.
President William Clinton's stay in Xi'an, a Foreign Ministry
spokesman said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Zhu Bangzao made the remarks at a meeting with
journalists. He was asked whether the public security
departments had arrested Yang Hai and other persons during
Clinton's stay in Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
"To my knowledge, none of the few people you mentioned were
arrested or detained during President Clinton's stay in Xi'an," he
said
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted, "It was quite normal for public security
staff to have a talk, according to law, with certain people who
had disturbed public order and obstructed the performance of
public duties."
</P>
<P>
"A few people's reports about this matter were pure
fabrications," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
