<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Worries Its Footballers' Fate in Spain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has expressed its worry over
its footballers' fate in Spain, after its team's Wednesday 1-3
loss to Paraguay edged Spain out of the ongoing World Cup in
France.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Bello, the Press Secretary to the Minister of Youth
and Sports, made his fear known Friday in Abuja to the official
News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"It is all over for the boys. You do not know these whites. You
will see what will happen to our boys in Spain next season," the
sports official said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the Spainish football association is already
complaining about the number of black players in their clubs. He
feared that Nigerian players may not be hired by Spanish clubs.
</P>
<P>
As it beat Bulgaria by 6-1, Spain needed Nigeria to draw with
Paraguay in Wednesday's match so that it can enter the second
round matches. Nigeria's loss made Paraguay qualify for the last
16 with 5 points as the runner-up in Group D, one point more than
Spain.
</P>
<P>
Bello noted that although there was no agreement between
Nigeria and Spain, the Spaniards had expected that the game
against Paraguay would be drawn.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear how many of Nigerian footballers play in Spain,
but it is known that Mutiu Adepoju and Finidi George, both major
players in Nigeria's World Cup squad, play for Spainish clubs in
the last season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
