<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Passes Bill to Penalize States for Missing Child </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 26 (Xinhua) -- A dozen states that missed
child support enforcement deadlines will be penalized under a bill
being sent to President Bill Clinton, although the fines are a
fraction of what a 1988 law required.
</P>
<P>
The bill marks an agreement between the House of
Representatives and Senate, which objected to penalties.
</P>
<P>
The Senate passed it Friday by voice vote. The House did the
same Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
A 1988 law required states to set up computer systems to track
the movements of parents who owe child support. More than 2.6
billion dollars have been spent on the project since then and the
deadline was extended once to give states until October to finish
their work.
</P>
<P>
States without working computer systems faced losing all
federal child support funding, which they use to manage the
collections.
</P>
<P>
But Friday's legislation substantially softens the penalties.
</P>
<P>
"Welfare recipients are now being held to strict time limits
and work rules," said Representative Clay Shaw Jr. a Republican
and chairman of the House Ways and Means human resources
subcommittee. "This bill says that states should be held to the
same level of accountability."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
