<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Aid Rwandan Reform Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 26 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) governing board has confirmed its support to the three-year
Rwandan macro-economic reform program, sources in the Finance
Ministry in Kigali said.
</P>
<P>
"The IMF's response to our program is an inspiring one, that
the ESAF (enhanced structural adjustment facility) is moving
toward success," said Prosper Musafiri, the director of
Macro-Economic Analysis in the Ministry of Finance and Economic
Planning, the Rwanda News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"It is an important stage for the program to be
approved by the IMF since it is going to encourage even other
donors to support it," the official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at an IMF meeting convened in Washington
on June 24 1998.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, the government of Rwanda sent a letter of
intent to the IMF board of governors seeking its support for the
program.
</P>
<P>
Through the letter, the government of Rwanda requested an IMF
funding amounting to 99.4 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
At the June 24 meeting, the IMF board approved a three year
credit for Rwanda equivalent to 95 million Dollars while 16.4
million Dollars will be disbursed, with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
According to Musafiri, the money will be specifically used for
balance of payment support channeled through the Central Bank to
stabilize foreign exchange reserve.
</P>
<P>
It will be mainly for private sector support by increasing
import capacity of private investors. The money is not designated
for government functions, he emphasized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
