<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece, Turkey Urged to Resolve Disputes Peacefully </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- U.S. presidential envoy for Cyprus
Richard Holbrooke urged Greece and Turkey Friday night to resolve
their disputes by peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a graduation ceremony at the American college in
Athens, Holbrooke warned that any use of violence would be
catastrophic for both Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He said that there should be permanent peace on both sides of
the Aegean Sea because the two countries had no problem in the
form of a clash of cultures.
</P>
<P>
While calling for the reduction in military spending by Greece
and Turkey, Holbrooke recommended international adjudication for
the resolution of the Imia islets issue which almost brought the
two countries to a war in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy said that his country would continue urging
Cypriot leaders to continue negotiations because the island
republic must not remain the last divided country in Europe.
</P>
<P>
As for Cyprus' accession to the European Union (EU), Holbrooke
said that Washington supported the island's EU application, but
also equally supported Turkey's hope for closer ties with Europe.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have been at odds for
decades over their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limit, the continental shelf in the Aegean Sea and the protracted
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Tension between Greece and Turkey rose recently following the
visits by Greek and Turkish warplanes to Cyprus in a show of
force.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980627.0289 </DOCNO>
