<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Wants ECOMOG to Intervene in Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 26 (Xinhua) -- Liberia has appealed to West
African leaders to intervene militarily through the sub-regional
peace-keeping force ECOMOG to restore peace in Guinea Bissau,
where rebellious troops claimed to have set up a junta.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here Friday quoted Liberian President
Charles Taylor as saying in a statement that "Liberia will
support the dispatch of an ECOMOG intervention force to Guinea
Bissau to restore peace and tranquillity to the people of that
sister republic."
</P>
<P>
"A collective regional initiative is necessary to buttress the
current efforts of Guinea and Senegal in Bissau," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
According to it, Taylor made the appeal in a telephone
conversation with General Abdulsalam Abubakar, Nigerian Head of
State and current Chairman of the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
The statement did not say if Liberia would contribute troops
to such an intervention force.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG was first formed in 1990 to intervene in the Liberian
civil war. Though it initially received strong resistance from
Taylor who started in the war in 1989, ECOMOG eventually
succeeded in ending Liberia's civil war in 1997, with Taylor
emerging winner of the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG also succeeded in helping restore the elected civilian
government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in Sierra Leone, where
it expelled the military junta of Paul Johnny Koroma that seized
power in a coup in May last year.
</P>
<P>
Guinea and Senegal have sent troops to quell a rebellion
against the government of President Bernardo Vieira led by the
country's sacked Army Chief of Staff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
