<HEADLINE> S. Africa, France Sign Pact on Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 26 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and France
signed three treaties Friday to enhance cooperation in merchant
shipping, police work and sports.
</P>
<P>
At the presence of South African President Nelson Mandela and
visiting French President Jacques Chirac, South African Transport
Minister Mac Maharaj and French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine
signed an agreement on merchant shipping and related maritime
matters in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine also signed an agreement on police cooperation with
his South African counterpart Alfred Nzo, and signed a sports
accord with South African Sports Minister Steve Tshwete.
</P>
<P>
Chirac, who had ended a visit to Namibia, arrived at Pretoria
Friday morning for a three-day state visit to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Before the signing of the accords, Chirac and Mandela held
talks for about an hour.
</P>
<P>
Chirac met South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki in the
afternoon to present him with the Grand Officer of the Legion of
Honor, the highest award in France for person ranked just after a
head of state.
</P>
<P>
Mandela hosted a state banquet in Chirac's honor in the
evening, at which he commended France for its contribution to
South Africa's economic development.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa's efforts to attain economic growth and
entrench democracy were strengthened by the knowledge that it
could be assured of French support, as a country and also as a
member of the European Union and of the United Nations Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday morning, Chirac will visit the Hector Peterson
Memorial in Soweto, a black township near Johannesburg, to
commemorate the historical 1976 students uprising before leaving
for Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
Chirac travels to Maputo, capital of Mozambique, on Sunday for
the next leg of his southern African tour before going to Angola.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
